"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420933","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","true","2015-10-19","<p>From 2016/17 all new eligible students living or studying in areas where household income is below the national average and who would otherwise have received a grant will <ins class="ministerial">qualify for an increased loan for living costs. The total living costs support available under the new student support arrangements for eligible students on the lowest incomes is increasing by 10.3% in 2016/17.</ins><del class="ministerial"> be eligible for a maintenance loan, that increases the total maintenance support available to them by 10.3%.</del></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-19T13:06:45.357Z","2016-04-20T10:36:58.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420933/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420933/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420933/answer/previousversion/23986","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420933/answer/previousversion/23986",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","Students: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect on students living or studying in areas where household income is below the national average of the announcement by the Chancellor of the Exchequer on 8 July 2015 that maintenance grants will be discontinued from 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","11570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420934","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-21","<p>During the 2010/11-2014/15 period, UK Trade and Investment (UKTI) recorded 8160 successful Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) projects won in the UK; of which 284 investments were in Scotland.</p><p>UKTI and its regional/local partners were involved in supporting 6415 of the total number of UK investments.</p><p>Breaking down the Scottish successes further, 5 landed in Kilmarnock and Loudoun.</p><p>UKTI works as one team with Scottish Government and all other regional and local partners, to promote and support inward investment into all parts of the UK.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-21T16:21:37.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420934/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420934/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","UK Trade and Investment: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of expenditure on UK Trade and Investment on the level of foreign direct investment in (a) the UK, (b) Scotland and (c) Kilmarnock and Loudoun constituency between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420935","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-26","<p>The data in the HM Treasury publication Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly, Statement of Funding Policywas compiled in 2010 using a different financial database system to the one subsequently used by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) and its delivery partners. The term ‘Research Establishments Major Capital funding’ is not currently used by BIS. Information on overall science capital expenditure is available in the Science Capital Roadmap, in the BIS annual accounts, and relevant information is also obtainable in Research Council Annual Reports (see below).</p><p><strong>Information on overall science capital expenditure is available in the BIS annual accounts and useful information is also obtainable in Research Council Annual Reports (see below). </strong></p><ol><li>BIS Annual Reports and Accounts <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bis-annual-reports-and-accounts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bis-annual-reports-and-accounts</a> The most recent report is here <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/444896/BIS-15-421-BIS-Annual-Report-15-web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/444896/BIS-15-421-BIS-Annual-Report-15-web.pdf</a></li></ol><p>See Annex B, page 200 for tables that features resource and capital spend on science and research.</p><ol start="2"><li>Research Council Annual Reports <a href="http://www.rcuk.ac.uk/about/aboutrcs/governance/" target="_blank">http://www.rcuk.ac.uk/about/aboutrcs/governance/</a></li></ol><p>Annual Reports for each of the Research Councils with information on expenditure.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-26T12:10:22.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420935/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420935/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the schedule of comparable programme objects in HM Treasury's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, what projects were funded by the Research Establishments Major Capital funding; what the (a) projected and (b) actual cost was of each of those projects; and whether each of those projects has been completed.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420936","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-28","<p>UK Trade and Investment expenditure is published annually in the UKTI Annual Report and Accounts which are available in the libraries of the House.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-28T17:47:35.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420936/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420936/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","UK Trade and Investment: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the schedule of comparable programme objects in HM Treasury's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, what the total expenditure was on UK Trade and Investment between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420937","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-27","<p>The data in the HM Treasury publication <em>Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales an Northern Ireland Assembly, Statement of Funding Policy</em>was compiled in 2010 using a different financial database system to the one subsequently in use by BIS and its delivery partners. This means that the information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost. However the UK Atomic Energy Authority, which is responsible for the UK fusion programme, has provided the following information.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Legacy costs<sup>1</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>JET decommissioning costs<sup>1, 5</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>8,279</p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>10,798</p></td><td><p>37</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>7,356</p></td><td><p>43</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>6,814 plus 1,050 capital<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>62</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>6,024 plus 1,554 capital<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>42</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>8,315 (est.) plus 6,010 capital<sup>2</sup> (est.)</p></td><td><p>166 (est.)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p><em>See note 3</em></p></td><td><p>214 (est.)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p><em>See note 3</em></p></td><td><p>943 (est.)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p><em>See note 3</em></p></td><td><p>16,306<sup>4</sup> (est.)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019/20</p></td><td><p><em>See note 3</em></p></td><td><p>28,251 (est.)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Notes</p><p>1. Figures in £000s.</p><p>2. Capital costs cover new facilities on the Culham site such as the Materials Research Facility and RACE (Remote Applications in Challenging Environments) funded partly through the National Nuclear Users Facility and Oxford City Deal.</p><p>3. Subject to next Spending Review.</p><p>4. The costs rise substantially in 2018/19 due to the expected closure of JET in 2018 and start of decommissioning. However this date is under review with the European Commission with an extension proposed.</p><p>5. These costs are undiscounted and form part of the total undiscounted liability for decommissioning JET of £256,544k as stated in the 2014/15 UKAEA Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-10-27T10:56:46.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420937/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420937/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","United Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the schedule of comparable programme objects in HM Treasury's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, what the total expenditure was on UKAEA-Decommissioning between 2010 and 2015; and what the forecast expenditure in which locations is on such decommissioning in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420938","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-20","<p>The decision to withdraw the 2015/16 English Speakers of Other Languages (ESOL) Plus (Mandation) funding was taken in the knowledge that providers could use their adult skills budget to continue to provide ESOL training for jobseekers and therefore mitigate any adverse impact. Our data showed that the numbers of claimants being referred to ESOL Plus (Mandation) provision was significantly lower than originally anticipated.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-20T10:26:16.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420938/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420938/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","Employment: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of reduction in funding to English for Speakers of Other Languages Mandation Courses on the level of employment among people for whom English is an additional language.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420939","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Government believes that naming schemes can be a useful tool for encouraging compliance with legislation. For example, a naming scheme for non-compliance with the National Minimum Wage has been in place since October 2013 and has named 285 employers to date.</p><p>The Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 introduced a new financial penalty for non-payment of employment tribunal awards to encourage the full and prompt payment of awards. The Government is considering what other levers could be used to support the effectiveness of this measure, including the potential of a naming scheme.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-16T13:54:31.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420939/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420939/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","Employment Tribunals Service: Enforcement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of introducing a scheme for naming and shaming employers who fail to pay an employment tribunal award.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","11618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420940","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-20","<br /><p>Eight financial penalties have been imposed on employers for aggravated breach of employment law, under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013, since its introduction on 6 April 2014.</p><br /><p>To date, two penalties have been paid and six remain unpaid although all penalties were imposed this year and further action is being considered.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-20T14:43:17.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420940/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420940/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","Employment Tribunals Service: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many financial penalties have been imposed on respondent employers under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013 to date; and how many such penalties (a) have been paid and (b) remain unpaid.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","11619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420941","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-10-21","<p>I have treated your question as asking for the average number of days taken to process remission applications since the introduction of fees. The information on remissions granted both fully and partially is available within the Ministry of Justice Official Tribunal Statistics and can be found at:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics</a>.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-10-21T10:02:18.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420941/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420941/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420941/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-10-13","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many days were taken to process and grant each application for readmission of employment tribunal fees that have been (a) granted and (b) partially granted since the introduction of those fees.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","11620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420942","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-22","<p>The Government will publish a full Impact Assessment alongside draft regulations to implement the National Living Wage.</p><p>As noted in Summer Budget 2015, at a firm level there is some evidence that previous increases in minimum wages in low paying firms may have been associated with increases in productivity.</p><p>Additionally, the Office for Budget Responsibility has published an estimate of the aggregate impact on productivity due to compositional change in the economy. They estimate an increase in hourly productivity in 2020 of 0.3 percentage points through this mechanism.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-10-22T14:14:39.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420942/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420942/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420942/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","Minimum Wage: Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment the Government has made of the potential effect on productivity of increasing the minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420943","Department for Work and Pensions","true","2015-10-19","<p>DWP’s contract with the Association of British Credit Unions Ltd to deliver the Credit Union Expansion Project began in May 2013. It <del class="ministerial">was</del><ins class="ministerial">is</ins> due to end in April 201<del class="ministerial">5</del><strong><ins class="ministerial">6</ins></strong> but we are currently considering a request for a<ins class="ministerial">n</ins> <del class="ministerial">further</del> extension. The Department has plans to review effectiveness at the end of the Project.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-19T13:14:22.517Z","2015-10-21T16:31:59.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420943/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420943/answer","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420943/answer/previousversion/24060","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420943/answer/previousversion/24060",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment has been made of the effectiveness of the Government's credit union expansion programme; and what assessment he has made of the feasibility of extending that programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","11604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420944","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>Expenditure figures for the House of Lords Appointment Commission are published in its annual reports which are available on its website at<a href="http://lordsappointments.independent.gov.uk/media/24714/annual%20report%202010-11%20final.pdf" target="_blank">http://lordsappointments.independent.gov.uk</a>.</p><p /> <p>Details about the Commission’s meetings are also available on its website.</p><br />","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-10-21T08:16:48.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420944/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420944/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-13","House of Lords Appointments Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much under each cost heading was spent on the House of Lords Appointments Commission between 2010 and 2015; and how many times that Commission met during that period.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420945","Cabinet Office","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Department for Culture Media and Sport is responsible for data protection policy and sponsorship of the Information Commissioner’s Office. This includes overall responsibility for the legal framework for data sharing under the Data Protection Act 1998. The Cabinet Office is leading on improving how data is accessed and shared across government.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-10-16T10:44:05.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420945/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420945/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-10-13","Data Protection: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which Department has responsibility for (a) data protection, (b) data sharing and (c) the Information Commissioner's Office.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","11785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420946","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>The government launched a comprehensive nationwide marketing campaign in late August. This will ensure that more people are aware of Pension Wise, of how it can help them, and that they can – and do – access high-quality, impartial guidance on making the most of the new pension flexibilities.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-21T13:42:05.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420946/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420946/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Pensions: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to promote Pension Wise.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420947","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is responsible for the regulation of financial services in the UK.</p><p>This is therefore a matter for the FCA, who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p>The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-16T13:35:05.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420947/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420947/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Financial Services: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to better regulate financial service providers working in the UK (a) in general and (b) specifically those selling off-shore services and investment opportunities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","11736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420948","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Government has established a criteria of eligibility for Help to Buy mortgages for participating banks to uphold. The responsibility of approving or rejecting a Help to Buy mortgage is given to participating banks.</p><p>There are currently two existing Help to Buy schemes; the Help to Buy: mortgage guarantee scheme and the Help to Buy: equity loan scheme. The eligibility criteria for each of these schemes can be found on the Help to Buy website: <a href="http://www.helptobuy.org.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.helptobuy.org.uk</a></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-16T13:36:48.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420948/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420948/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many Help to Buy mortgages have been refused by the Government despite being accepted by the participating bank.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","11741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420949","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Government does not collect information on the number of Help to Buy mortgage applications declined on the basis of a poor credit rating.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-16T13:30:46.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420949/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420949/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many Help to Buy mortgages have been declined on the basis of a poor credit rating.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","11739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420950","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<ol><li>By July 2015 the Valuation Office Agency had cleared over 94% of outstanding business rates appeals as of 30 September 2013 in England. The Agency continues to focus on clearing outstanding appeals. In order to further improve the efficiency of the Agency, the Government will introduce a more structured, rigorous and transparent appeals system as part of this session’s Enterprise Bill. <br></li><li>The business rates retention scheme in England is providing real incentives for councils to support enterprise and economic growth. In 2015-16, 362 authorities expect to retain an extra £544 million in business rates above baseline funding. Under the scheme, local authorities or pools of local authorities are protected against significant declines in business rates income through a safety net that guarantees income at 92.5% of baseline funding. And in a radical reshaping of the state we will ensure that by the end of the Parliament the local government sector will retain 100% of local taxes to spend on local government services.</li></ol>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-21T16:06:14.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420950/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420950/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Valuation Office Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the (a) efficiency of the Valuation Office Agency (VOA) and (b) potential merits of providing emergency payments to councils who face budgeting difficulties due to the time taken by the VOA to re-assess business rates.","false","Biography information for Mark Garnier","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","11512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420951","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>Principle 3.2.7, as set out in the 2010 edition of the Statement of Funding Policy, encompassed business rates income and council tax revenues collected by Scottish local authorities.</p><br /><p>The Statement of Funding Policy is reviewed and updated periodically. The devolved administrations have been informed that the Treasury expects to publish a revised version on 25<sup>th</sup> November to coincide with the Spending Review announcement.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","11497 ; 11498","2015-10-21T13:37:27.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420951/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420951/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to principle 7 in paragraph 3.2 of his Department's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, which areas of self-financed expenditure of the Scottish Parliament are included in that principle.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420952","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>Principle 3.2.7, as set out in the 2010 edition of the Statement of Funding Policy, encompassed business rates income and council tax revenues collected by Scottish local authorities.</p><br /><p>The Statement of Funding Policy is reviewed and updated periodically. The devolved administrations have been informed that the Treasury expects to publish a revised version on 25<sup>th</sup> November to coincide with the Spending Review announcement.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","11496 ; 11498","2015-10-21T13:37:27.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420952/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420952/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 2.25 of his Department's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, when he expects the statement of funding policy to be next updated.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420953","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>Principle 3.2.7, as set out in the 2010 edition of the Statement of Funding Policy, encompassed business rates income and council tax revenues collected by Scottish local authorities.</p><br /><p>The Statement of Funding Policy is reviewed and updated periodically. The devolved administrations have been informed that the Treasury expects to publish a revised version on 25<sup>th</sup> November to coincide with the Spending Review announcement.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","11496 ; 11497","2015-10-21T13:37:27.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420953/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420953/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to principle 7 in paragraph 3.2 of his Department's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, whether he plans to include that principle in an updated statement of funding policy.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420954","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>Information relating to the total cost of Royal travel is readily available in the annual financial reports. They include a full breakdown of costs for Royal Travel for each of the years in question.</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.royal.gov.uk/TheRoyalHousehold/Royalfinances/AnnualFinancialReports/Annualfinancialreports.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.royal.gov.uk/TheRoyalHousehold/Royalfinances/AnnualFinancialReports/Annualfinancialreports.aspx</a></p><br /><p>The Statement of Funding Policy no longer contains information on Royal Travel costs.</p><p><br></p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-21T13:59:15.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420954/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420954/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Royal Family: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the schedule of comparable programme objects in his Department's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, what the total cost was of royal travel between May 2010 and May 2015.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420955","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>The information requested is not held centrally by HM Treasury and the cost of providing it would exceed the disproportionate cost threshold.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-21T13:38:11.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420955/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420955/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the schedule of comparable programme objects in his Department's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, what projects were funded by the PFI Special Grant; and what the total capital cost was of each of those projects.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420956","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-21","<p>Local authorities are free to use Revenue Support Grant as they see fit in support of their statutory functions. Whilst the Department collects information on revenue and capital spending by local authorities, it does not ask authorities for information on the particular use to which they put Revenue Support Grant, or any of the other revenue sources available to them.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-21T13:55:44.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420956/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420956/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the schedule of comparable programme objects in his Department's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, what projects were funded by the revenue support grants; and what the total capital cost was of each of those projects.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420957","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>The information requested can only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-10-21T13:39:00.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420957/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420957/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to expenditure on (a) HMRC: Administration, (b) HMRC: Tax and rate collection, (c) HMRC: Valuation Office, and (d) HMRC: Treasury in the schedule of comparable programme objects in his Department's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, (i) how much of that expenditure in which locations was on (A) property and (B) personnel and (ii) how many people in which locations were employed through such expenditure between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420958","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>Information on the business rates paid by GP surgeries is not held centrally. My Department continues to work with authorities affected by the business rates appeals on GP surgeries to understand the impact on local authority finances.</p><p>Under the business rates retention scheme, local authorities or pools of local authorities are protected against significant declines in business rates income through a safety net that guarantees income at 92.5% of baseline funding.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-10-20T15:47:59.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420958/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420958/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","GP Surgeries: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect on local councils of the revaluation of business rates levied on GP surgeries.","false","Biography information for Mark Garnier","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","11540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420959","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-16","<p>The latest information on the number of tax credit recipients under 25 in the UK can be found in table 3.1 of the April 2015 Personal Tax Credits published statistics, found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-tax-credits-provisional-statistics-2013-to-2009" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-tax-credits-provisional-statistics-2013-to-2009</a></p><p>These statistics are published in April and December each year.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-10-16T13:38:48.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420959/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420959/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Welfare Tax Credits: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people under 25 years old in (a) St Helens North constituency, (b) Merseyside and (c) the UK receive tax credits.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","11553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420960","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not calculate separately the cost of collecting revenues paid over to the EU each year. Revenues paid over to the EU are funded through paying over a proportion of the customs duties and general taxation that are collected by HMRC.</p><br />","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","11544","2015-10-21T16:03:29.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420960/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420960/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","EU Budget","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of the work required to collect the revenue paid into the EU budget in each year since 1985.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","11543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420961","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not calculate separately the cost of collecting revenues paid over to the EU each year. Revenues paid over to the EU are funded through paying over a proportion of the customs duties and general taxation that are collected by HMRC.</p><br />","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","11543","2015-10-21T16:03:29.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420961/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420961/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","EU Budget","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of the work required to collect the revenue paid into the EU budget each year.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","11544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420962","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>As the Chancellor of the Exchequer, my right hon. Friend the Member for Tatton (Mr Osborne) has noted, the best outcome for the UK economy is that we achieve major economic reform of the EU. The Prime Minister is focused on success: he believes he can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU, and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis.</p><br /><p>The Confederation of British Industry and British Chambers of Commerce have both come out to say they support the reform agenda the Prime Minister is seeking to deliver.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-21T16:08:29.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420962/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420962/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on foreign direct investment of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","11562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420963","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Department has engaged with the social care sector, including care providers, to understand how the introduction of the National Living Wage will affect them. The overall costs of providing social care will be considered as part of the Spending Review later this year.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-10-21T14:58:33.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420963/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420963/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Home Care Services: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect on the future of the private sector home care industry of the implementation of the national living wage.","false","Biography information for Dr James Davies","Vale of Clwyd","Dr James Davies","11609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420964","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-16","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. As has been the practice adopted by previous administrations it is not Government policy to normally release details of such meetings.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","11622","2015-10-16T13:44:56.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420964/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420964/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Treasury: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with the Minister for Finance in the Republic of Ireland; and what subjects were raised at those discussions.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","11621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420965","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-16","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. As has been the practice adopted by previous administrations it is not Government policy to normally release details of such meetings.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","11621","2015-10-16T13:44:56.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420965/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420965/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Treasury: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with the Ministers for Finance and Foreign Affairs in the Republic of Ireland; and what subjects were raised at those discussions.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","11622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420966","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-16","<p>Information regarding the UK’s allocation from the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF), European Social Fund (ESF), and European Agricultural Fund for Rural Development (EAFRD), including how these will be divided across England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales for the period 2014-2020, is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/2010-to-2015-government-policy-european-funds/2010-to-2015-government-policy-european-funds" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/2010-to-2015-government-policy-european-funds/2010-to-2015-government-policy-european-funds</a>.</p><p>Information regarding the UK’s allocation from the European Agricultural Guarantee Fund (EAGF), including how this will be divided across England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales for the period 2014-2020, is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-cap-allocations-announced" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-cap-allocations-announced</a>.</p><p>Information regarding the UK’s allocation from the European Maritime and Fisheries Fund, including how this will be divided across England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales for the period 2014-2020, is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/european-fisheries-fund-allocated-to-promote-growth-across-the-uk" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/european-fisheries-fund-allocated-to-promote-growth-across-the-uk</a>;</p><p>Information regarding the UK’s share from European Territorial Cooperation, including the regions in which the funds will be spent, is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/european-territorial-cooperation-programmes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/european-territorial-cooperation-programmes</a></p><p>Information regarding the UK’s share from the Youth Employment Initiative, including the regions in which the funds will be spent, is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/170-million-to-help-young-people-find-jobs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/170-million-to-help-young-people-find-jobs</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-16T13:47:08.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420966/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420966/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","EU Budget","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much funding the UK has been allocated from the (a) European Regional Development Fund, (b) European Social Funds, (c) European Agricultural Fund of Guarantee, (d) European Agricultural Fund for Rural Development, (e) European Territorial Cooperation, (f) Youth Employment Initiative and (g) European Maritime and Fisheries Fund for the period from 2014 to 2020; and what information his Department holds on how much funding has been allocated from each fund in each region.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","11588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420967","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-16","<p>The information requested for points a, b, d, e, f, and g is set out in the financing plans in the respective programmes for these funds which can be found on gov.uk, gov.scotland and gov.wales.</p><p>The information requested for point c can be found on the European Commission and Eur-lex websites.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-16T13:45:27.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420967/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420967/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","EU Budget","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much funding the UK was allocated from the (a) European Regional Development Fund, (b) European Social Funds, (c) European Agricultural Fund of Guarantee, (d) European Agricultural Fund for Rural Development, (e) European Territorial Cooperation, (f) Youth Employment Initiative and (g) European Maritime and Fisheries Fund in the period from 2010 to 2014.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","11589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420968","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Government has not made a specific assessment of the benefits to UK businesses in these sectors as a result of the UK’s membership of the WTO. But the benefits will be substantial as over the 20 years of the WTO average applied tariffs have been cut in half from 15 per cent in 1995 to less than 8 per cent today. And there are now 161 WTO Members comprising 98% of world trade, with the new (post-1995) members contributing 21% of this total. Further benefits are likely from negotiations currently underway: for example the Information Technology Agreement 2 (ITA2) should liberalise tariffs that affect around £12 billion of UK exports and imports.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-16T13:42:58.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420968/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420968/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","Import Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the benefits to UK businesses in the (a) retail, (b) automobile, (c) construction, (d) ICT, (e) financial services and (f) defence sectors of reduced tariff barriers arising from UK membership of the World Trade Organisation.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","11590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420969","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-16","<p>The cumulative impact of all concluded, on-going and potential trade negotiations currently being undertaken by the EU could boost UK GDP by over £ 20 billion in the long run.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-16T13:41:20.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420969/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420969/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","EU External Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the benefit to the UK economy of the preferential trade agreements the EU has negotiated with countries outside the EU.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","11591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420970","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-10-16","<p>The EU provides the biggest single market in the world. EU countries trade twice as much with each other as they would without it. The absence of tariffs contributes to this. The single market also brings benefits for consumers. For example, between 2000 and 2006, the cost of making a 10-minute call in the EU fell by an average of 74%, and roaming charges will be abolished completely in 2017. As part of our agenda for EU reform, we want to go further and faster on economic competitiveness including liberalisation of the services sector, trade, and de-regulation.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-10-16T13:40:24.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420970/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420970/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-10-13","EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the benefits to the UK economy of (a) the absence of tariff barriers for intra-EU trade and (b)  other aspects of the single market.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","11592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420971","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Government provides generous tax incentives to help new and innovative businesses in the UK, including the automotive and motor racing industries. The rate of corporation tax is currently 20% and will be 18% in 2020, the lowest of any economy in the G20.</p><br /><p>The Government supports research and development (R&amp;D) in the automotive and motor racing industries through R&amp;D tax reliefs. At Summer Budget 2015, the Government also announced that it would increase the permanent level of Annual Investment Allowance to £200,000 which will further support investment in plant and machinery.</p><br /><p>The Government has also committed £86 million through the Advanced Propulsion Centre to secure Britain’s strength in the research, development and commercialisation of low carbon vehicle technologies.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-10-21T16:07:43.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420971/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420971/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Business: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to provide tax incentives for businesses seeking to enter the automotive and motor racing industries.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420972","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Government has legislated to ensure that the Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) and Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), are fully empowered to maintain the integrity of the ring-fence, and to take action in preventing this type of misconduct.</p><br /><p>The ring fencing regime includes requirements that directors of the ring-fenced body (RFB) be able to take decisions independently of group entities; that transactions with group entities be on arm’s length terms; and that arrangements with other group entities should be managed as with third parties.</p><br /><p>The PRA and the Bank of England have powers to take action if such a transaction were to have a potential impact on the prudential resilience or resolvability of the RFB. The FCA can also take enforcement action for breaches of its rules or for these types of market abuse, which includes the imposition of substantial financial penalties.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-21T13:39:49.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420972/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420972/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Financial Conduct Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the Financial Conduct Authority acts to prevent companies from fraudulently using capital raised from selling ring-fenced bonds to bail out poorly-performing parent companies.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420973","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Office for National Statistics does not publish data on problem debt in the UK. According to the latest figures published by the Office for National Statistics, unsecured debt as a proportion of income currently stands at 37 per cent in Q2 2015, down from its pre-crisis peak of 46 per cent in Q1 2007.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-21T13:40:30.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420973/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420973/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the level of problem debt in the UK.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","11776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420974","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>The IMF’s report concludes that risks to global financial stability from emerging markets remain elevated, amid falling risk appetite and increasing market liquidity risks.</p><p>The UK Government is alive to any implications of these risks for UK financial stability. The Government established the Financial Policy Committee (FPC) to identify and manage these types of risk to the UK financial system.</p><p>The Bank of England’s forthcoming 2015 stress test of the UK banking system will assess its resilience to a deterioration in global economic conditions, particularly in emerging markets.</p><p>Furthermore, the UK’s financial regulatory bodies are continuing to work at an international level on risks relating to global financial market liquidity.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-21T13:43:18.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420974/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420974/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the most recent Global Financial Stability Report from the IMF.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420975","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer stated his intention to return Lloyds Banking Group to the private sector over the coming year in his Mansion House speech of June 2015. The proposal to launch a retail sale in Spring 2016 is consistent with this commitment.</p><br /><p>The Government is determined to build a share-owning democracy and to continue to reduce the national debt by making Lloyds shares available to the public. Final decisions around the timing of a sale are dependent on market conditions, among other factors.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-21T13:41:21.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420975/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420975/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Lloyds Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the reasons are for the timing of his Department's sale of the remaining £2 billion of Lloyds' shares.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420976","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-22","<p>In 2014, UK goods exports to China were worth £15.5bn, making China our 6<sup>th</sup> largest goods export partner. The government wants to improve this relationship, with a target for China to be the 2<sup>nd</sup> largest recipient of UK exports within a decade.</p><br /><p>The Government warmly welcomes the State Visit of President Xi and Madame Peng, an important milestone that should lay the foundations for a golden age in the bilateral relationship. The Visit will build upon the sustained engagement by the Chancellor and other Ministers to deepen UK-China economic cooperation, including via the annual, Chancellor-led Economic and Financial Dialogue (EFD).</p><br /><p>At the most recent EFD in September 2015, both sides agreed a package of measure to strengthen their long-term collaboration, including on capital markets, bond markets, green finance, asset management and insurance. Further detail can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/462412/EFD_factsheet.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/462412/EFD_factsheet.pdf</a></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-22T14:49:38.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420976/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420976/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Foreign Relations: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to improve Britain's economic ties with China.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420977","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-21","<p>Troubled Families Outcomes Plans are locally designed and owned documents that state how each local authority will demonstrate significant and sustained progress against the whole range of complex problems that a family on the programme may have. We have no current detailed analysis of child sexual exploitation and abuse within all Outcome Plans, but the programme is designed to be flexible so that all local authorities can bring in families where they believe child sexual exploitation or sexual abuse is an issue, and they believe the family would benefit from being included on the programme<em>.</em></p><br />","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2015-10-21T14:01:49.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420977/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420977/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Families: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many local authorities in phase two of the Troubled Families programme have made tackling (a) child sexual exploitation and (b) sexual abuse an outcome in their Troubled Families Outcome Plan.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","11682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420978","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Secretary of State has not held any meetings with Derby City Council in connection with the re-development of brownfield land or the funding made available to local authorities to develop local development orders for housing on brownfield land in January.</p><p>Derby City Council did not submit a bid to the £4.4 million fund.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-20T15:44:47.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420978/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420978/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Derelict Land: Derby","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with Derby City Council on the re-development of brownfield sites in the city with support from the grant announced on 28 January 2015 to help develop such sites following the announcement of a £4.4 million fund to help unlock potential sites.","false","Biography information for Amanda Solloway","Derby North","Amanda Solloway","11629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420979","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-16","<p>Data on the number of dwellings by tenure and district can be found in Live Table 100 which is available to download at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants</a></p><p>The Department collects its data on household income from the English Housing Survey which does not go down to the district level.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-16T13:43:06.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420979/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420979/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420979/answer/previousversion/23762","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420979/answer/previousversion/23762",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Social Rented Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many households occupy social housing in each London borough; and how many such households in each such borough have an annual income above £40,000.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","11723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420980","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>The total numbers of local authority and private registered provider (housing association) dwellings by local authority district can be found in Live Table 100 which is available to download at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants</a> This shows the numbers as at 1 April 2014, a proportion of which may have the Right to Buy, Preserved Right to Buy, the Right to Acquire or may become eligible with the voluntary agreement with housing associations depending on exemptions and eligibility of tenants.</p><p>Data on the numbers of right to buy sales by district up to June 2015 can be found in Live Table 691 which is available to download at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housing-sales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housing-sales</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-20T15:46:40.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420980/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420980/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Social Rented Housing: Worcester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of households in Worcester eligible to purchase their homes under (a) the right to buy, (b) the retained right to buy, (c) the right to purchase and (d) the new voluntary right to buy agreement with registered social landlords.","false","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","11667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420981","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Help to Buy: ISA is an expansion to the existing Help to Buy scheme. The Help to Buy: ISA scheme will be launched on 1 December 2015.</p><p>The existing Help to Buy schemes are the Mortgage Guarantee scheme and Equity Loan scheme. Over 110,000 housing completions have taken place with the support of the Help to Buy scheme, as of June 2015.</p><p>The Help to Buy: mortgage guarantee scheme has been running since October 2013. Figures are available only for completions to June 2015. There have been 110 completions in Worcester as of June 2015. Data for Worcestershire is not reported. The latest data is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/help-to-buy-mortgage-guarantee-scheme-quarterly-statistics-october-2013-to-june-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/help-to-buy-mortgage-guarantee-scheme-quarterly-statistics-october-2013-to-june-2015</a>.</p><p>The Help to Buy: equity loan scheme has been running since April 2013. In Worcester, there have been 183 completions with the support of the Help to Buy: equity loan scheme, as of June 2015. Data for Worcestershire is not reported. Official statistics on completions for the Help to Buy: equity loan scheme, monthly, broken down by local authority for England, are available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/help-to-buy-equity-loan-scheme-monthly-statistics" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/help-to-buy-equity-loan-scheme-monthly-statistics</a></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-16T13:37:46.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420981/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420981/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-10-13","Help to Buy Scheme: Worcestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people in (a) Worcester and (b) Worcestershire have taken up a Help to Buy ISA.","false","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","11668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420982","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-19","<p>We have allocated funding of £1million in 2015/16 (through the Tenant Empowerment Programme) to support social housing tenants' involvement in their local communities. This includes support to those who wish to manage delivery of services to their homes and estates by taking up their Statutory Right To Manage.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-19T14:16:53.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420982/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420982/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to promote tenant management.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","11634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420983","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-16","<p>No. DWP does not differentiate between social and private landlords in the manner in which it makes direct payments of rent to landlords on behalf of tenants who receive universal credit.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-16T13:47:23.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420983/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420983/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Universal Credit: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department differentiates between private sector landlords and housing associations in the manner in which it makes direct payments to landlords on behalf of tenants who receive universal credit.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","11600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420984","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>How an authority should determine whether or not someone is intentionally homeless is set out in legislation and statutory homelessness guidance, which is available to the public and authorities. It makes clear that housing authorities should consider each case in light of its particular facts and must not adopt general policies which seek to pre-define circumstances that do or do not amount to intentional homelessness. We have no plans to carry out a review.</p><p>Homelessness legislation ensures that families and the most vulnerable always have a roof over their head. This includes cases where households have made themselves homeless and are assessed by a local authority as being in priority need for accommodation. The law places a duty on the authority to secure suitable accommodation for a period that enables the household a reasonable opportunity to secure their own accommodation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","11495 ; 11545","2015-10-20T15:39:54.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420984/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420984/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will commission an independent inquiry into the practice of classifying people as intentionally homeless.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420985","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>How an authority should determine whether or not someone is intentionally homeless is set out in legislation and statutory homelessness guidance, which is available to the public and authorities. It makes clear that housing authorities should consider each case in light of its particular facts and must not adopt general policies which seek to pre-define circumstances that do or do not amount to intentional homelessness. We have no plans to carry out a review.</p><p>Homelessness legislation ensures that families and the most vulnerable always have a roof over their head. This includes cases where households have made themselves homeless and are assessed by a local authority as being in priority need for accommodation. The law places a duty on the authority to secure suitable accommodation for a period that enables the household a reasonable opportunity to secure their own accommodation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","11495 ; 11579","2015-10-20T15:39:54.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420985/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420985/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department provides to (a) the public and (b) councils on the definition and application of the classification of intentional homelessness.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420986","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>The business rates retention scheme in England is providing real incentives for councils to support enterprise and economic growth. In 2015/16, 362 authorities expect to retain an extra £544 million in business rates above baseline funding. Under the scheme, local authorities or pools of local authorities are protected against significant declines in business rates income, such as from rating appeals on GP surgeries, through a safety net that guarantees income at 92.5% of baseline funding.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","11539","2015-10-20T15:49:38.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420986/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420986/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","GP Surgeries: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to provide financial assistance to local authorities to deal with unforecastable shortfalls arising from the revaluation of business rates levied on GP surgeries.","false","Biography information for Mark Garnier","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","11538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420987","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-20","<p>The business rates retention scheme in England is providing real incentives for councils to support enterprise and economic growth. In 2015/16, 362 authorities expect to retain an extra £544 million in business rates above baseline funding. Under the scheme, local authorities or pools of local authorities are protected against significant declines in business rates income, such as from rating appeals on GP surgeries, through a safety net that guarantees income at 92.5% of baseline funding.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","11538","2015-10-20T15:49:38.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420987/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420987/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","GP Surgeries: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he plans to take to help local councils with pooled funding tackle unpredicted revenue shortfalls due to the revaluation of the business rates levied on GP surgeries.","false","Biography information for Mark Garnier","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","11539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420988","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-16","<p>This Government is determined to extend home ownership to anyone who aspires to own their own home.</p><p>Shared ownership has proven to be extremely popular and has played an important role in helping families who are otherwise priced out of the market. This is why between April 2010 and March 2015 we have delivered 41,000 new shared ownership homes through the Affordable Homes Programme.</p><p>The Government is committed to ensuring that shared ownership continues to be effective at helping hard working families meet their aspiration to own their own home. This is why earlier this year we consulted on a range of possible proposals to streamline the process for selling on shared ownership properties.</p><p>As a result we have simplified the process for resale of shared ownership properties by removing the pre-emption right, or right of first refusal for housing providers, from those former shared ownership homes where the owner has 'staircased' to 100% ownership.</p><p>But there is more that can be done and the Government is currently looking at how we can make shared ownership even more accessible as a route to full home ownership.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-16T12:56:46.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420988/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420988/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Shared Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to reduce barriers preventing tenants in shared ownership properties from staircasing up to increase the share of the property they own; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","11756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420989","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-10-16","<p>A local housing authority can, through licensing of Houses in Multiple Occupation and other privately rented properties (selective licensing), impose conditions relating to the management of the premises so its use does not adversely impact upon its vicinity. Since 27 March 2015 an authority can make a selective licensing scheme in an area where (a) it has recently, or is experiencing, a high level of migration into the private rented sector and (b) the scheme will help preserve or improve the social or economic well-being of that area.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-10-16T12:47:58.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420989/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420989/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-10-13","Private Rented Housing: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to assist local authorities to safeguard the residential amenity of urban residential locales with high numbers of private sector lettings; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","11749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420990","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Government is looking at ways to ensure that newly built premises get at least superfast broadband connectivity, including legislation if necessary. We are discussing this with telecoms infrastructure providers and developers. But it is for the market to determine the most appropriate technology that should be used.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-21T09:29:19.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420990/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420990/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-13","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2015 to Question 10535, what steps he is taking specifically to encourage the deployment of fibre to the premises in new build housing developments.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","11787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420991","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-19","<p>The pricing of tickets is a matter for the clubs to decide on, however we would encourage all clubs, whether in the Premier League or not, to think carefully about affordability for all fans when setting their ticket prices.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-10-19T15:00:24.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420991/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420991/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-13","Football: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will hold discussions with the FA about the affordability of tickets to Premier League matches for people on the national average wage.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","11532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420992","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-10-19","<p>DWP’s expenditure figures on TV licences for the over 75s can be found in table 1a of the ‘summer budget’ link <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2015</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-10-19T12:38:46.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420992/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420992/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-10-13","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the cost to the public purse was of television licences for people over the age of 75 in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","11548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420993","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-15","<p>The Government’s consultation on the balance of payments between pay TV platforms and Public Service Broadcasters (PSBs) closed on 30 June 2015. The consultation examined the flow of payments between PSBs and pay TV platforms, and whether regulations relating to these transactions are necessary to ensure broadcasters can deliver the highest quality content, at the best price, to the widest possible audience. Department for Culture, Media and Sport officials are now analysing with a view to publishing a Government response in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-15T09:44:26.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420993/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420993/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-13","Television: Royalties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that payment of royalties is made by platform providers to broadcasters as well as to the rights-holders of programmes.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","11547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420994","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-22","<p>All local BDUK project are required to have project websites providing information to their residents of the roll out plans for their area. All projects include maps of their intervention areas and regular updates on progress. The majority of projects have seven digit postcode checkers on their site to provide greater localised information. Details for Cheshire’s broadband rollout can be found on the Connecting Cheshire postcode checker (<a href="http://www.connectingcheshire.org.uk/check-availability" target="_blank">http://www.connectingcheshire.org.uk/check-availability</a>) and on deployment maps indicating broader timescales for upgrades (<a href="http://www.connectingcheshire.org.uk/connecting-cheshire-deployment-maps" target="_blank">http://www.connectingcheshire.org.uk/connecting-cheshire-deployment-maps</a>).</p><br />","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-22T09:31:17.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420994/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420994/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-13","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to ensure that (a) Connecting Cheshire and (b) other local authority partnerships provide timely and accurate advice to homes and businesses about when work will take place to connect them to superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","11572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420995","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-19","<p>It is a matter for Ofcom to monitor and regulate competition in electronic communications markets and periodically to review the operation of the markets. The Regulator announced in March this year a Strategic Review of Digital Communications in the UK. Maintaining and promoting competition in the telecommunications market is a key area that it is considering, as set out in theDiscussion Document Ofcom[O1]published in July. This can be found at<a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/consultations/dcr_discussion/summary/digital-comms-review.pdf" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/consultations/dcr_discussion/summary/digital-comms-review.pdf</a></p><p>The European Commission has just begun a review of the Electronic Communications regulatory Framework. The promotion of competition in the telecommunications sector is high on the UK’s list of objectives for this review.</p><p>The UK remains a highly competitive market. It has the lowest available stand alone fixed broadband cost among the six biggest countries in Europe, the average price of a residential fixed broadband package has fallen by 40% in real terms between 2004 and 2014. The UK also hasthe second cheapest mobile tariffs. There are over a dozen companies offering fixed broadband services, either over their own infrastructure or through local loop unbundling. In mobile, as well as the 4 major mobile network operators, there are over 40 virtual network operators offering services.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-10-19T16:30:55.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420995/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420995/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-13","Telecommunications: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to promote competition in the telecommunications market.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","11722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420996","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-19","<p>The Rugby World Cup is expected to attract 466,000 international visitors to England – more than any previous RWC. Research from Visit Britain tells us that sport tourists traditionally stay for longer, have a propensity to travel around the country and spend more money when doing so. International visitors are expected to contribute up to £869 million in direct expenditure to the UK economy. Last year, an economic impact study by EY estimated a boost of almost £1bn to the UK’s GDP (of £2.2bn total spend generated). This includes £85m of infrastructure projects and the support of 41,000 jobs.</p><p>There are strong plans to drive legacy benefits from the tournament. The Rugby Football Union (RFU) is working to spread the game's popularity and there are also plans around the host cities to maximise economic and community benefits.</p><p>The RFU's plans to grow the game include:</p><br /><ul><li>improving facilities through £10m investment</li><li>investing in people, including by recruiting and training nearly 3,000 referees and over 3,000 new coaches, and recruiting 6,000 volunteers ('the Pack') to help run the tournament</li><li>increasing schools’ participation in rugby, especially state schools. 130,000 new state school pupils have played rugby, of whom a third are girls and of whom 3,000 are now playing regularly for a club</li><li>attracting 16-24 year old players back to clubs</li><li>promoting touch rugby to appeal to more people</li><li>the Unity Project to promote rugby in Europe’s developing rugby nations; and</li><li>cultural engagement through over 700 rugby themed events and celebrations.</li></ul><br /><p>DCMS and the Government continue to be fully supportive of these plans.UK Trade &amp; Investment (UKTI) is coordinating a Rugby World Cup Business Festival programme of activity across 8 of 9 regions, aligned to the locations of fixtures. A Global Investment Conference (GIC), hosted by UKTI, launched the festival on 17 September 2015 at Lancaster House. This brought together government leaders and 150 senior potential and existing investors from 9 key Foreign Direct Investment target market countries with teams competing in the tournament.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","11925","2015-10-19T15:16:57.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420996/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420996/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-13","Rugby: World Cup","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans his Department has to promote the legacy of the 2015 Rugby World Cup.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420997","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-19","<p>Around 25,000 adults already participate in motorsports each week in England and with support this number could increase further. Motor sports and motor cycling clubs and associations are eligible to apply to Sport England for funding and I would encourage them to consider this as an option to help increase participation.</p><br /> <br />","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-10-19T16:52:48.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420997/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420997/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-10-13","Motor Sports: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to increase participation in motor sport for young people from families with lower incomes.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420998","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-20","<p>Secretary Carter and I discussed a range of issues including current operations, Russia, and the Strategic Defence and Security Review. We discussed ways in which we can further strengthen our collaboration and agreed to work together on a combined approach to defence innovation.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-10-20T14:28:50.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420998/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420998/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-13","USA: Official Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what key policy aims he achieved during the recent visit to the UK by the US Secretary of Defense.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420999","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-20","<br /><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" rowspan="5"></td><td colspan="6" rowspan="5"><p>I am withholding the information as its disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br />","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-10-20T14:24:34.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420999/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/420999/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-13","Iraq: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether UK Tornadoes flying missions over Iraq are armed with heat-seeking air-to-air missile systems.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421000","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-20","<br /><p>Russian military aircraft are not conducting combat operations in Iraqi airspace: The British Defence attache in Moscow has therefore provided no information to the Russian Government on this subject.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-10-20T14:19:20.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421000/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421000/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-13","Iraq: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information the British Defence Attaché to Russia has provided to the Russian government on measures taken to ensure accidental engagement with Russian military aircraft flying in Iraqi airspace does not lead to engagement in military confrontation.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421001","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-20","<p>There are no plans to review the Army's Rules of Engagement in response to the court martial of Sergeant Blackman. Rules of Engagement (ROE) are Operation not Service specific and set out the legal and policy constraints within which all UK forces must work. UK forces receive mandatory training in order to ensure that they understand the responsibilities and obligations placed on them by ROE profiles and UK and international law.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-10-20T14:22:27.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421001/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421001/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-13","Alexander Blackman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if his Department will review the Army's rules of engagement in response to the court martial of Sergeant Blackman.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421002","Ministry of Defence","true","2015-10-20","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my hon. Friend the Minister for Reserves (Mr Brazier) on 20 July 2015 to Question number 7353 to the hon. Member for North Durham (Mr Kevan Jones).</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-10-20T14:21:56.66Z","2015-10-21T16:33:16.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421002/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421002/answer","Hansard Extract 20 July 2015.docx","Hansard Extract 20 July 2015.docx","Army","Army","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421002/answer","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421002/answer/previousversion/23980","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421002/answer/previousversion/23980","Hansard Extract 20 July 2015.docx","Army","11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-13","Army","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many regular soldiers he plans to maintain in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421003","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-20","<p>I have not held discussions with my Russian counterpart.</p><p>I have regular conversations with my US counterpart on a range of subjects, including the campaign against ISIL, and most recently met him on 9 October 2015. As my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has said, there is a strong case to do more against ISIL in Syria, but the UK will not join Coalition air strikes against ISIL in Syria without the endorsement of Parliament.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","11713","2015-10-20T14:17:47.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421003/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421003/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-13","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with his (a) Russian and (b) US counterparts on the extension of British airstrikes to Syria.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421004","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-10-16","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the written statement released by my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Defence (Michael Fallon) on 12 October 2015,titledFuture Unmanned Air Systems Capability.</p><p>The Government has taken an early decision in the Strategic Defence and Security Review to commit to the Protector programme. The programme is currently in its assessment phase, so detailed work is continuing to confirm a contract for the airframe and associated details, including date for the capability's entry into service and acquisition and life support cost profile, following which the Ministry of Defence will be better placed to understand the implications for the UK workforce and supply chain.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","11582 ; 11593 ; 11594 ; 11596 ; 11603 ; 11610","2015-10-16T13:03:26.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421004/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421004/answer","Hansard Extract Monday 12 October 2015.docx","Hansard Extract Monday 12 October 2015.docx","Future Unmanned Air Systems Capability","Future Unmanned Air Systems Capability","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421004/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-10-13","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he plans for Protector programme unmanned aerial vehicles, and each individual aircraft commissioned under that programme, to enter into service.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","11595"
