"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421029","Department for Education","false","2015-10-16","<p>Average per pupil revenue funding figures for Devon are given below. With the introduction of the dedicated schools grant (DSG) in 2006-07, the changes to the funding mechanism meant figures were no longer available to be shown split by phase of education.</p><p>Figures for financial years 2005 to 2013 are shown below. These are in cash terms:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Average revenue per pupilfunding (cash)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2005-06 (baseline)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2006-07</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2007-08</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2008-09</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009-10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Devon LA (£)</strong></p></td><td><p>3,560</p></td><td><p>3,800</p></td><td><p>4,050</p></td><td><p>4,220</p></td><td><p>4,430</p></td><td><p>4,680</p></td><td><p>4,600</p></td><td><p>4,600</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>These are in real terms using September 2015 GDP deflators in 2014-15 prices:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Average revenue per pupil funding (real)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2005-06 (baseline)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2006-07</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2007-08</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2008-09</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009-10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Devon LA (£)</strong></p></td><td><p>4,370</p></td><td><p>4,530</p></td><td><p>4,700</p></td><td><p>4,770</p></td><td><p>4,880</p></td><td><p>5,010</p></td><td><p>4,850</p></td><td><p>4,770</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Per pupil figures use DSG allocations plus other schools related grants, e.g. school standards grant, school standards grant (personalisation), standards fund, and pupils aged 3-15 rounded to the nearest £10. Most of the additional grants were mainstreamed into DSG in 2011-12.</p><p>The changes to DSG funding in financial year 2013 to 2014 with funding allocated through three blocks (namely schools, early years and high needs) means there is no longer a comparable overall figure with previous years. The table below shows the DSG schools block unit funding figures in cash and real terms for Devon LA.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>DSG schoolsblock per pupil funding (£)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Devon LA (cash) </strong></p></td><td><p>4,156</p></td><td><p>4,156</p></td><td><p>4,342</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Devon LA (real)</strong><sup> <strong>[1]</strong></sup></p></td><td><p>4,215</p></td><td><p>4,156</p></td><td><p>4,299</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><sup>[1] </sup>Real terms figures shown in 2014-15 prices using GDP deflators at 30.09.15.</p><p>Since 2011-12 schools have received the Pupil Premium which targets funding at pupils from the most deprived backgrounds to help them achieve their full potential. In 2011-12, the Premium was allocated for each pupil known to be eligible for universal infant free school meals (UIFSM), looked after children and children of parents in the armed services. In 2012-13 coverage was expanded to include pupils known to have been eligible for Free School Meals at any point in the last six years. The amounts per pupil for each type of pupil are shown in following table in cash terms:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Pupil Premium per pupil (£)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Free School Meal Pupil Primary</strong></p></td><td><p>£488</p></td><td><p>£623</p></td><td><p>£953</p></td><td><p>£1323</p></td><td><p>£1320</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Free School Meal Pupil Secondary</strong></p></td><td><p>£488</p></td><td><p>£623</p></td><td><p>£900</p></td><td><p>£935</p></td><td><p>£935</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Service Children</strong></p></td><td><p>£200</p></td><td><p>£250</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>LookedAfter Children</strong></p></td><td><p>£488</p></td><td><p>£623</p></td><td><p>£900</p></td><td><p>£1900<sup>[2]</sup></p></td><td><p>£1900<sup>[2]</sup></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><sup>[2] </sup>Also includes children adopted from care.</p><p>Total Pupil Premium allocations for Devon local authority for each year are shown in the following table in cash terms:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Pupil Premium Allocations (£ millions)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16 (prov.)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Devon</strong></p></td><td><p>5.486</p></td><td><p>11.161</p></td><td><p>17.221</p></td><td><p>22.942</p></td><td><p>23.220</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>These figures in real terms:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Pupil Premium Allocations (£ millions)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16 (prov.)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Devon</strong></p></td><td><p>5.786</p></td><td><p>11.559</p></td><td><p>17.467</p></td><td><p>22.942</p></td><td><p>22.990</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Price Base: Real terms at 2014-15 prices, based on GDP deflators as at 30.09.2015.</p><p>The table below shows capital funding for the financial years that are available. The data is in cash terms as allocations are phased across more than one year making real terms calculations meaningless. Complete information on the split of capital between phases of education is not held centrally.</p><table><thead><tr><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Devon £m</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Capital allocations</strong></p></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p>2005-06</p></td><td><p>30.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>53.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>68.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>56.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>71.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>31.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>31.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>37.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>48.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>42.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16 (prov.)</p></td><td><p>10.2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Notes:</p><ul><li>Capital allocations includes capital grant and supported borrowing allocations.</li><li>Figures are rounded to the nearest £100,000.</li><li>Funding in 2015-16 is still subject to project progress and is therefore subject to change. The funding figures provided for 2015/16 only include formulaic programmes and payments to date. Further funding is yet to be released for capital programmes dependent upon project progress and this has not been reflected in the figures.</li></ul>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-10-16T13:16:25.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421029/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421029/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-10-13","Pupils: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much (a) revenue and (b) capital funding was provided to per pupil in state (i) primary and (ii) secondary schools in Devon (A) in cash terms and (B) at 2015 prices in each financial year since 2005-06.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421030","Department for Education","false","2015-10-21","<p>We want all children to lead healthy and active lives. Physical Education (PE) is a compulsory subject at all four key stages in the national curriculum. The programme of study makes clear that a high-quality PE curriculum should provide opportunities for pupils to become physically confident in a way which supports their health and fitness.</p><p>Through the introduction of the primary PE and Sport Premium in 2013, primary schools will have received over £450 million of ring-fenced funding to improve the quality of their PE and sport provision.</p><p>The Department of Health provided £1.5 million this year to fund Change4Life Sports Clubs which target less active children in primary schools. An independent evaluation published on 19 October 2015in 2012/13 found that over two years the number of children who were active for at least 60 minutes every day was 69 per cent higher after 12 weeks in the Change4Life primary schools sports clubs than it was when they started. Researchers estimate that this represents an additional 33,000 children achieving this level over the life of the programme. Since 2011, 270,000 primary school children have benefitted from the sports clubs. The report can be found at: <a href="http://www.canterbury.ac.uk/social-and-applied-sciences/human-and-life-sciences/spear/docs/change-4-life-final-report.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.canterbury.ac.uk/social-and-applied-sciences/human-and-life-sciences/spear/docs/change-4-life-final-report.pdf</a></p><p>We are working closely with the Department of Health and the Department for Culture, Media and Sport on their respective forthcoming strategies on childhood obesity and sports. The strategies will tackle childhood obesity and increase the number of people participating in sport and wider physical activity.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-10-21T15:20:53.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421030/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421030/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-10-13","Physical Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to improve physical fitness standards in schools.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421031","Department for Education","false","2015-10-19","<p>The government recognises that service leavers have a wealth of skills and experiences that have been proven to be transferable to the classroom, including teamwork, leadership and the ability to inspire and engage. Former armed forces personnel model attributes such as self-discipline and resilience.</p><p>The University of Brighton, who are contracted to run the programme, continue to promote Troops to Teachers through a range of methods including service leaver employment fairs.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-10-19T15:34:47.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421031/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421031/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-10-13","Teachers: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she plans to take to increase the number of former Armed Forces personnel who retrain as teachers through the Troops to Teachers programme.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","11732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421032","Department for Education","false","2015-10-21","<p><br>The department does not publish information from the October school census, and instead publishes information from the January census which is the only one of the termly censuses that covers all school types and collects information on class sizes. We collect data on pupils but not on places in schools. Data from the January 2016 school census will be published in June 2016.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-10-21T11:34:02.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421032/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421032/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-10-13","Primary Education: Lambeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will publish the October 2015 census data for primary school reception class places for each school in the London Borough of Lambeth.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","11677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421033","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-20","<p>A number of communication meetings, seminars, and reciprocal visits have taken place under the Memorandum of Understanding. No projects have as yet been taken forward.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-10-20T13:29:41.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421033/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421033/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-13","Nuclear Power: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, which projects have been undertaken to date under the UK-China Memorandum and Understanding on Enhancing Cooperation in the Field of Civil Nuclear Industry Fuel Cycle Supply; and what the (a) location and (b) cost is of each such project.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421034","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Centre of Nuclear Excellence is a Cumbrian partnership of public and private organisations which aims to maximise the benefit of the region’s nuclear capability and expertise for the local economy and UK as a whole. The organisations involved support the initiative’s work with in-kind contributions of manpower.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-10-20T15:24:59.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421034/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421034/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-13","Nuclear Centre of Excellence: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the annual budget is for the UK's Centre of Nuclear Excellence.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421035","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Joint Research and Innovation Centre (JRIC) is envisaged to be the subject of a commercial agreement between the National Nuclear Laboratory and the Chinese National Nuclear Corporation.</p><p>These two organisations are still in the process of negotiating such an agreement and will need to consider details on the structures, funding, governance and accountability of the JRIC. As such, it is too early for Government to be able to comment on the outcomes of such a negotiation.</p><p>We continue to maintain an interest in developments of these discussions and will work, where appropriate, with our counterparts in the Chinese government to ensure that outcomes are mutually beneficial to the research landscape of both nations.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","11649 ; 11650","2015-10-16T14:00:50.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421035/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421035/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-13","Nuclear Power: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether the activities of the new UK-China joint research and innovation centre will be subject to oversight by (a) the Office for Nuclear Regulation and (b) her Department's national nuclear stakeholder forum.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421036","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Joint Research and Innovation Centre (JRIC) is envisaged to be the subject of a commercial agreement between the National Nuclear Laboratory and the Chinese National Nuclear Corporation.</p><p>These two organisations are still in the process of negotiating such an agreement and will need to consider details on the structures, funding, governance and accountability of the JRIC. As such, it is too early for Government to be able to comment on the outcomes of such a negotiation.</p><p>We continue to maintain an interest in developments of these discussions and will work, where appropriate, with our counterparts in the Chinese government to ensure that outcomes are mutually beneficial to the research landscape of both nations.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","11648 ; 11649","2015-10-16T14:00:50.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421036/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421036/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-13","Nuclear Power: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether all projects undertaken in the new UK-China joint research and innovation centre will be subject to the (a) Freedom of Information Act 2000 and (b) Environmental Information Regulations 2004.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421037","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>A number of international oil and gas companies are involved in the current exploration around Falkland Islands waters which is expected to continue into 2016. The results of exploration will be announced at the appropiate time by the companies concerned.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-10-21T15:05:42.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421037/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421037/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Oil: Falkland Islands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent progress has been made on extracting potential oil reserves near the Falklands; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421038","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Joint Research and Innovation Centre (JRIC) is envisaged to be the subject of a commercial agreement between the National Nuclear Laboratory and the Chinese National Nuclear Corporation.</p><p>These two organisations are still in the process of negotiating such an agreement and will need to consider details on the structures, funding, governance and accountability of the JRIC. As such, it is too early for Government to be able to comment on the outcomes of such a negotiation.</p><p>We continue to maintain an interest in developments of these discussions and will work, where appropriate, with our counterparts in the Chinese government to ensure that outcomes are mutually beneficial to the research landscape of both nations.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","11648 ; 11650","2015-10-16T14:00:50.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421038/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421038/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421038/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-13","Nuclear Power: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what new departmental resources have been committed to support the UK-China joint research and innovation centre; which UK personnel have been appointed to this work to date; what process was followed in making those appointments; and where each such post was advertised.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421039","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-20","<p>The total expenditure on the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority (NDA) between 2010 and 2015 was £15,381 million. This was predominantly spent on front-line operations and decommissioning with a small central spend on the NDA itself and on activities such as R&amp;D. The expenditure was across the NDA estate which covers England, Scotland and Wales. However, it should be noted that Sellafield, the UK’s largest, most complex and challenging site accounts for over half of the NDA’s annual budget. There are no nuclear facilities in Northern Ireland.</p><br /><p>TheDepartment’s request for future funding as part of the Spending Review contains details of the NDA’s estimates of expenditure in line with its existing plans. This includes focussing on tackling the highest hazards at Sellafield.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-10-20T15:25:43.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421039/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421039/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421039/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-13","Nuclear Decommissioning Authority: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the schedule of comparable programme objects in HM Treasury's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, what the total expenditure was on the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority between 2010 and 2015; and what the forecast expenditure is in each location on that authority in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421040","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-16","<p>Any changes which we make to the feed-in tariff (FIT) scheme as a result of the FIT review, which is currently open for consultation until 23<sup>rd</sup> October, will only apply to new applicants entering the scheme after the necessary legislation to effect the changes has passed through Parliament.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-10-16T13:40:32.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421040/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421040/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421040/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-13","Renewable Energy: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether the announced reductions in feed-in tariff support will apply to existing contracts or new ones; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","11742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421041","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-16","<p>Good progress is being made on processing Basic Payment Scheme 2015 applications including capturing changes that were made on the paper forms along with any new requirements of the scheme onto the Rural Payments IT system. We currently have access to around 800 people to perform this processing work.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-10-16T10:02:47.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421041/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421041/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421041/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-13","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress has been made on (a) processing farmers' 2015 Basic Payment Scheme applications and (b) tackling the challenges of getting information supplied by farmers in paper form back onto an online validation process; and what resources have been committed to carry out this work to date.","false","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","11734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421042","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-16","<p>The move to the paper based application approach for the Basic Payment Scheme 2015 has not had an impact on the validation and verification of claims and the Rural Payments Agency remain on track to make the majority of payments in December.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-10-16T09:57:07.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421042/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421042/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421042/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-13","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what effect the switch to a paper-based application system for the Basic Payment Scheme has had on (a) claim validation and the verification of claims and (b) the delivery of timely payments from 1 December.","false","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","11735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421043","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-22","<p>The table below shows the total expenditure on animal diseases in the five years from 2010-11 to 2014-15.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>Spend (£)</p></td><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>117,001,623</p></td><td><p>88,876,234</p></td><td><p>87,903,416</p></td><td><p>84,648,922</p></td><td><p>80,724,477</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br />","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-10-22T11:01:57.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421043/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421043/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-13","Animals: Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the schedule of comparable programme objects in HM Treasury's publication, Funding the Scottish Parliament, National Assembly for Wales and Northern Ireland Assembly: Statement of Funding Policy, published in October 2010, what the total expenditure was on animal diseases between 2010 and 2015; and to what projects in which locations that funding was provided.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","11511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421044","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Rural Payments Agency remains on track to meet their public payment commitments. Full payments on the majority of Basic Payment Scheme 2015 claims will be made from December, within the payment window that runs between December and June. As such interim payments are not being considered.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-10-16T09:59:46.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421044/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421044/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421044/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-13","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to introduce interim payments in cases in which there are delays in making payments under the Basic Payments Scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","11598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421045","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-16","<p>Countryside Stewardship has introduced significant rationalisation with regard to its predecessors; integrating three legacy schemes into one. At the same time the number of environmental management options available has been reduced by 70% and the number of capital items by 20%.</p><p>Most of the elements in Countryside Stewardship (higher tier; woodland and water capital grants) remain largely analogous to their predecessor schemes. However, the application process has been inevitably more complex than intended given the need for a paper based application system this year.</p><p>The stricter EU control rules have resulted in greater reliance on record keeping and other documentary evidence to demonstrate compliance but we have already published guidance on the controls applicable to the scheme in order to clarify the requirements.</p><p>We will evaluate this first year of the scheme and simplify it wherever possible.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-10-16T12:14:38.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421045/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421045/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421045/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-13","Countryside Stewardship Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment she has made of the level of complexity of the Countryside Stewardship Scheme; if she will take steps to simplify that scheme; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","11599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421046","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Framework document between Defra and Kew is currently in draft. Defra and Kew are working in line with the draft Framework document, which sets out how the bodies work together but is not legally binding. Defra is looking at how it works with its arm’s length bodies and this may inform the finalisation of the document.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-10-20T15:17:39.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421046/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421046/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421046/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-13","Royal Botanic Gardens Kew","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will place in the Library a copy of the framework agreement between her Department and the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421047","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-16","<p>Seafish does not spend its levy, directly or through other bodies, on promoting the fishing industries of other North Sea or Norwegian Sea countries. At the request of the four Fisheries Ministers, Seafish introduced a transparent process in 2012 to agree priorities for spending. Seafish consults UK Industry Panels to ensure that all parts of the UK seafood sector benefit proportionately from the levy raised. These activities are set out in the Seafish Corporate Plan, which can be found on the Seafish website.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-10-16T09:38:31.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421047/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421047/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421047/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-13","Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to ensure that (a) Seafish and (b) other bodies funded by fishing levies do not promote the fishing industries of other North Sea or Norwegian Sea countries.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","11556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421048","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-16","<p>Seafish does not use levies raised on fish caught by the UK catching sector to promote the fishing industries of other countries. Levy is raised at the first point of sale in the UK, including on imported fish, and is used to support the UK seafood industry.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-10-16T09:45:01.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421048/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421048/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421048/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-13","Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make an assessment of the amount spent each year by (a) Seafish and (b) other bodies funded by fishing levies on promoting the fishing industries of other countries.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","11557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421049","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-10-20","<p>In recognition of the need for a better understanding of the potential impacts of underground coal gasification, the Department has commissioned an assessment of the greenhouse gas emissions related to underground coal gasification, which we expect to publish in due course.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-10-20T13:31:23.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421049/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421049/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421049/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-10-13","Coal Gasification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment her Department has made of the environmental effects of underground coal gasification.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","11541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421050","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-16","<p>The EU itself does not carry out tests on the effects on bees from the use of neonicotinoid insecticides.It makes decisions on the regulation of neonicotinoids and other pesticides on the basis of scientific information provided by companies working to agreed standards and published scientific studies.</p><p>The European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) has published scientific opinions on the risks from uses of these pesticides following mandates from the European Commission. EFSA also recently held a consultation calling for data on this matter as the first step in an EU review of controls on these insecticides.The UK is contributing fully to this review.</p><p>EFSA documents are published on its website (<a href="http://www.efsa.europa.eu/" target="_blank">http://www.efsa.europa.eu/</a>).</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-10-16T09:47:27.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421050/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421050/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421050/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-13","Bees: Neonicotinoids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish the results of the EU's recent tests on the likely harmful effects to bees of the use of neonicotinoids; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","11724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421051","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-10-16","<p>The application window for the Mid-Tier closed on 30 September. 2,314 agreement applications were received. 1,025 expressions of interest for the Higher Tier have also been received, together with 257 applications for forestry agreements. The level of interest is in line with our expectation.</p><p>Natural England and the Forestry Commission are now working to assess these to offer agreements to those applicants who have submitted high quality plans that will do most to improve our water quality and the farmed environment</p><p>Some elements of the scheme have been available earlier in 2015. 1,798 applications were received for 2015 water capital grants, of which 1,458 have been awarded. We also received 743 applications for woodland creation during a fixed application period and for tree health and woodland management plans, which continue to be applied for year round. To date, 288 agreements have been awarded.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-10-16T09:51:32.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421051/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421051/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-10-13","Countryside Stewardship Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the level of take-up of the Countryside Stewardship Scheme is; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","11725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421052","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>We continue to urge Russia, both in public and through diplomatic channels, to focus its efforts on ISIL targets. The EU Foreign Affairs Council on 12 October also called on Russia immediately to cease targeting the moderate opposition.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-21T15:52:44.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421052/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421052/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he plans to take to deter Russian forces from targeting non-IS targets in Syria.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421053","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Philip Hammond) discussed Russia’s military build-up in Syria with Secretary of State John Kerry at the UN General Assembly last month. Government ministers and officials discuss Syria with their American counterparts on a regular basis, and have shared concerns over Russia’s strikes on non-ISIL targets in Syria. The UK and US, together with France, Germany, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Turkey, issued a statement on 2 October expressing concern about Russian strikes in Syria, calling on Russia to stop attacking the Syrian opposition and civilians, and to focus on fighting ISIL.</p><br />","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-21T15:53:52.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421053/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421053/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his US counterparts on the targeting of non-IS targets by Russian forces in Syria.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421054","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","true","2015-10-21","<p>The UK strongly condemns ISIL’s wanton destruction of cultural heritage in Syria and Iraq, including in Palmyra. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office helped secure UN Security Council Resolution 2199 which obliges all UN Member States to prevent the trade in Iraqi and Syrian cultural property that has been illegally removed from those countries.</p><p>But strong words and legal frameworks are not enough. As a key player in the Global Counter ISIL Coalition, the UK is committed to degrading and defeating ISIL, including through military action. By checking ISIL’s advance, the Coalition’s air campaign and support for partner military forces in Iraq and Syria has had the effect of protecting key historical sites in both countries. However, there is inevitably a limit to what we can do. The only way of safeguarding all historic sites from ISIL is by defeating them politically and militarily. That requires continued effort by the Global Coalition, as well as a more inclusive political settlement in Iraq, and an end to the conflict in Syria.</p><p>On 28 October I will be co-hosting a summit with the Secretary of State for the Department of Culture, Media and Sport, my Rt. Hon. Friend the Member for <del class="ministerial">Bromsgrove</del> <ins class="ministerial">Maldon </ins>(Mr <ins class="ministerial">Whittingdale</ins><del class="ministerial">Javid</del>) on Cultural Heritage Protection.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-21T15:57:36.09Z","2015-10-23T13:26:36.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421054/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421054/answer","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421054/answer/previousversion/24960","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421054/answer/previousversion/24960",,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Islamic State: Cultural Heritage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to prevent ISIL from destroying valuable historical sites in Palmyra and elsewhere.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421055","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>The UK and Australia continue to enjoy a close and productive partnership. At the heart of this are regular dialogues between Ministers on important policy issues. Our shared values and interests mean that dialogues continue even as counterparts change. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) most recently spoke to Malcolm Turnbull on 8 October. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) is also in regular contact with his Australian counterpart.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-10-19T15:33:50.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421055/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421055/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Australia: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Australian counterpart on the effect of Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull coming into office on Australian-UK relations.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421056","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>On 8 October the Special Representative of the Secretary-General and Head of the United Nations Support Mission in Libya (UNSMIL), Bernardino León, announced details of the proposed final political settlement in Libya. This included: names for the Prime Minister and five others members of the Presidential Council, the final text of the Political Agreements, and twelve other names proposed for ministerial positions.</p><p>We are working closely with international partners to encourage the Libyan parties to endorse the proposal. UNSMIL hope to achieve formal signature before 20 October.</p><p>We are working tirelessly in support of UN efforts to establish a Government of National Accord in Libya. Negotiations remain difficult. But only an inclusive government will deliver the peace and stability that the Libyan people desire and deny the space for ISIL and other extremist groups to operate.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-21T12:09:18.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421056/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421056/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Libya: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of progress on the (a) establishment of a national unity government in Libya and (b) ending of political instability in that country.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421057","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Government supports progress towards a peaceful and prosperous Zimbabwe, where the rule of law and human rights are upheld, laying the foundations for long-term sustainable development. We frequently urge the Zimbabwean government to implement the new constitution agreed in 2013, which provides a foundation for improved governance and human rights, and to make necessary reforms to the electoral system to resolve the shortcomings identified by Southern African Development Community and the African Union observer mission during the 2013 elections. The UK also continues to support democracy by working with civil society organisations, human rights defenders and other stakeholders.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-10-20T13:02:24.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421057/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421057/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Zimbabwe: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he plans to take to encourage a return to representative, democratic governance in Zimbabwe once Mr Mugabe ceases to hold the office of President.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421058","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>The State Visit by Chinese President Xi Jinping on 20-23 October will set the tone and agenda for our relationship with China for the next decade, to develop a global partnership responding to the opportunities and challenges of the 21st Century. The visit will deliver major economic benefits for Britain through business deals, science and innovation co-operation, and enhanced links in education and culture. It will highlight the strength of the relationship in several areas: our openness to business links, our aim to make our economies fit for the future, and our response to important global issues.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-10-20T14:35:27.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421058/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421058/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","China: State Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his Department's aims are for the state visit of President Xi Jinping in October 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421059","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>We are deeply concerned by the recent spate of attacks and clashes across the Occupied Palestinian Territories and Israel. Officials at our Embassy in Tel Aviv discuss the situation frequently with Israeli officials. Most recently, on 12 October, the UK Charge d'Affaires raised our concerns with Israel’s Deputy Defence Minister, making clear that it is imperative that both sides actively de-escalate the tensions.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-21T12:20:42.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421059/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421059/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Israeli counterparts on recent outbreaks of violence in Israel and Palestine.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421060","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-22","<p>The government continues to monitor closely developments in Turkey. We acknowledge Turkey’s right to defend itself against terrorist attacks, whoever the perpetrator. We welcome reports of a PKK (Kurdistan Workers' Party) ceasefire and hope that peace talks will resume soon. It is vital that the parliamentary elections on 1 November pass without further incident.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-10-22T15:06:14.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421060/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421060/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Turkey: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effects of recent political instability in Turkey.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421061","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>The constitutional status of the Territories was reviewed prior to the publication of the 2012 White Paper: Security, Success and Sustainability. We believe that the fundamental structure of our constitutional relationship is the right one, with powers devolved to the elected governments of the Territories to the maximum extent possible consistent with the UK retaining those powers necessary to discharge its sovereign responsibilities.</p><br />","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-10-20T13:00:10.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421061/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421061/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","British Overseas Territories: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the current level of representation of the British Overseas Territories at Westminster; and whether his Department plans to increase such representation and adopt a model similar to that used in (a) France and (b) the Netherlands.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421062","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-22","<p>We are working with our EU partners in tackling those criminal elements who are involved in migrant smuggling and human trafficking. The EU Naval Forces Operation in the Mediterranean (EUNAVFOR Med – shortly to be renamed Operation Sophia) was launched on 22 June and is now in its second phase which aims to locate, interdict and seize smuggling vessels, and detain suspected smugglers, on the high seas. The UK has been one of the largest EU contributors to this mission. HMS ENTERPRISE has been deployed since 4 July and she will shortly be joined by HMS RICHMOND with her organic Lynx helicopter, Royal Marines boarding party and Unmanned Aerial Vehicle for enhanced surveillance.</p><p>A recently passed United Nations Security resolution, (http://www.un.org/en/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=S/RES/2240(2015), endorses our actions on the high seas under the EUNAVFOR Med operation. The UK was at the forefront of securing this resolution.</p><p>In addition, the UK’s multi-agency Organised Immigration Crime (OIC) Taskforce builds on existing extensive law enforcement capability in the UK and overseas focusing on the crime networks in source countries, transit points including the Mediterranean as well as at the UK border and France. The Taskforce is already working with international partners, actively sharing intelligence and progressing criminal investigations.</p><p>The OIC Taskforce builds on the existing progress made by Immigration Enforcement and others to tackle the gangs that target the most vulnerable. Last year UK law enforcement disrupted more than 170 organised crime gangs involved in immigration crime while so far this year, Immigration Enforcement alone has seen 48 convictions and the disruption of 27 organised crime gangs.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-10-22T15:12:30.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421062/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421062/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Mediterranean Sea: Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of recent UK efforts to prevent people smuggling in the Mediterranean.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421063","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>The attack on a NATO convoy on 11 October is a reminder of the threat under which our troops in Afghanistan continue to work, in partnership with the Afghan Government and others in the international community, to build and sustain a peaceful and democratic Afghanistan. We always seek to draw on knowledge and experience acquired as a result of such incidents. Our commitment as part of the NATO mission and in honour of those who have given so much in this endeavour is unwavering.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-21T12:11:54.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421063/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421063/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Afghanistan: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the attack on UK military vehicles in Kabul on 11 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421064","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>We welcome Japan’s recent security reforms, which will allow Japan to play a greater role in international peace and security. During his visit in August, the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), discussed with the Japanese Foreign Minister the opportunities these reforms will create for even closer bilateral cooperation.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-10-20T14:34:02.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421064/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421064/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Japan: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Japanese counterparts on security reforms in that country.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421065","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>We enjoy a close security dialogue with the National Unity Government in Kabul. The Commander Joint Forces Command, the Deputy Chief of the Defence Staff and the Secretary of State for Defence, my right hon. Friend the Member for Sevenoaks (Mr Fallon) have all visited Afghanistan recently to discuss the security situation with Afghan counterparts. When the Afghan National Defence and Security Forces (ANDSF) assumed full responsibility for national security at the end of 2014, we and they understood that there would inevitably be testing times ahead. The ANDSF have responded well. The Taliban attack on the city of Kunduz was a setback for ANDSF, but government forces have regained control of the city. NATO will be working with the Afghan Government to identify lessons from this incident and the fighting season more broadly. NATO and the UK remain committed partners of the Afghan Government. The Taliban should accept President Ghani’s invitation now to end the fighting and join the peace process.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-21T15:59:32.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421065/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421065/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Afghanistan: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policy of recent military defeats by Afghan forces; and what discussions he has had with his Afghan counterparts on the insurgency at Kunduz.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421066","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>We have made representations to the Government of Israel stating that it is vital that the longstanding status quo in respect of access to Temple Mount/Haram al Sharif, and other historic sites, be preserved. In recent weeks, Her Majesty's Ambassador in Tel Aviv raised this with senior Israeli officials and the Israeli President. Our National Security Adviser also raised this with his Israeli counterpart. Most recently, on 12 October, the Charge d'Affaires at our Embassy in Israel raised this issue with Israel’s Deputy Defence Minister, requesting that restrictions on visitors be lifted.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-21T13:38:06.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421066/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421066/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Jerusalem","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Israeli counterpart on the recent conflict at Temple Mount.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421067","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>Her Majesty's Government provides counter-narcotics assistance to a range of international partners, including Afghanistan. We do so to tackle the international drugs trade and minimise the threat it poses to the UK. Our work involves the sharing of operational information and expertise and the provision of capacity building. It is important to protect activities which form part of the UK's contribution to the international counter-narcotics effort and to respect the principle that international partners are able to operate in secrecy on matters of national security against organised crime. As such, it is our policy not to disclose specific details of our counter narcotics work, as to do so risks reducing its effectiveness and damaging international relations.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-10-21T16:00:08.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421067/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421067/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Afghanistan: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to prevent the export of illegal drugs from Afghanistan.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421068","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>We have been at the forefront of the humanitarian response to the crisis in Syria, having committed over £1.1bn, which includes funding for regional countries to assist arriving refugees.</p><p>The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), recently visited Lebanon and Jordan, where he paid tribute to the efforts of these countries in hosting Syrian refugees. Syria’s neighbours have been incredibly generous in welcoming huge numbers of refugees. There are now over four million Syrian refugees in the region, including over one million who fled Syria in 2014 alone. Turkey hosts the highest number of refugees, at over 2 million, followed by Lebanon at over 1 million and Jordan at over 628,000. The UK has allocated £559 million to support refugees in the region and vulnerable host communities to date, including £304 million in Lebanon and £193 million in Jordan. The Gulf States continue to contribute generously to humanitarian support for the Syria crisis, and there are large numbers of Syrians already in the Gulf.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-21T12:06:22.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421068/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421068/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he has taken to encourage other nations in the Levant and Arabian peninsula to accept refugees from Syria.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421069","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>As a cornerstone of the international rules-based system, the UN is a universally recognised platform for countries to reach agreement on the global issues that affect us all. The opening session of the UN General Assembly brings together political leaders from across the world in a way that sets the multilateral agenda for the year ahead. Since the opening of the General Assembly’s 69th session in September 2014, notable achievements in support of UK policy aims include: a new set of global development goals to help eradicate extreme poverty within the next 15 years; support for the Secretary General to develop a comprehensive Plan of Action to Prevent Violent Extremism; a General Assembly resolution on the Arms Trade Treaty which maintained momentum towards the Treaty’s entry into force in 2014; strong human rights resolutions on Syria and the Democratic Peoples’ Republic of Korea; and $220m (£145m) in savings on peacekeeping mission costs.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-10-21T15:55:33.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421069/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421069/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","UN General Assembly","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what policy aims his Department achieved at the 69th session of the UN General Assembly.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421070","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-22","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend, the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond ) raised unlawful incursions with the Spanish government when he visited Spain in February. The Government has raised a number of serious unlawful incursions directly with the Spanish government at a senior level in recent months. I did this most recently on 12 September during a meeting with the Spanish Minister for Europe, Fernando Eguidazu Palacios.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-10-22T15:13:31.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421070/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421070/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Gibraltar: Spain","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Spanish counterpart on incursions into Gibraltarian waters by Spanish ships in recent months.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421071","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>The Government opposes the death penalty in all circumstances, especially in cases which do not meet the minimum standards defined by the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights. We believe it undermines human dignity and there is no evidence that it works as a deterrent. Ministers, our Ambassador in Riyadh and the Embassy team raise the issue of the death penalty with the Saudi authorities, both bilaterally and through the European Union.</p><p>We recognise that total abolition of the death penalty is unlikely in Saudi Arabia in the near future. Our focus is therefore on encouraging the introduction of EU minimum standards for the death penalty as a first step, and on supporting access to justice and rule of law.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-20T15:01:44.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421071/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421071/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Saudi Arabia: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Saudi Arabian counterpart against that country's policy of judicially-sanctioned capital punishment.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421072","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-19","We are extremely concerned by the high levels of sexual violence in Syria and within Syrian refugee camps. The UN Commission of Inquiry report of September 2015 highlighted widespread sexual abuse carried out by the Syrian regime, ISIL and some armed opposition groups within Syria. Assad’s forces and militia are responsible for the vast majority of sexual violence, which include threats, rape, degrading body searches and sexual harassment in prisons and branches of the security agencies. ISIL propaganda condones the barbaric treatment of male and female captives, sexual relations with adolescent girls and sexual slavery. Unfortunately, many of those who flee the conflict remain extremely vulnerable to sexual violence. Exploitation of vulnerable individuals within refugee camps was highlighted by the UN Equity for Gender Equality and Empowerment of Women report “We keep Silent” issued in April 2014. The UK is providing £1 billion in humanitarian aid, which includes support to the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) to provide services for survivors of sexual violence and has so far reached over 27,000 women in Syria. We are also supporting case management in Jordan for over 800 survivors and cash assistance to vulnerable refugee women in Lebanon. The FCO has committed £5.2 million to projects preventing sexual violence in Syria. We are supporting projects to train health professionals and human rights defenders in collecting and preserving evidence of human rights abuses including sexual violence.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-19T14:08:51.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421072/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421072/answer","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421072/answer/previousversion/23902","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421072/answer/previousversion/23902",,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Syria: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment the Government has made of the level of sexual violence (a) within Syria and (b) in camps for Syrian refugees.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","11597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421073","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","We are not able to give a running commentary on the discussions. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) is focussed on success. He believes he can and will succeed in reforming and renegotiating our relationship with the EU and campaigning to keep the UK in the EU on that basis. I welcome Chancellor Merkel’s statement to the Bundestag on 15 October that “it goes without saying that we will work constructively with the British government” on this question, and that she was “convinced that we will be able to find an acceptable compromise”.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-10-21T14:06:48.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421073/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421073/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress was made during the recent visit of German Chancellor Angela Merkel on negotiations on the UK's relationship with the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421074","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>The British government regularly raises its human rights concerns with the Saudi Arabian authorities at the highest levels through Ministers, our Ambassador, and the Embassy team in Riyadh.</p><p>Saudi Arabia remains a Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office country of concern because of the human rights situation in the country, particularly on the use of the death penalty, restricted access to justice, restrictions on women’s rights, as well as on freedom of expression, freedom of assembly and freedom of religion or belief. We regularly make our views well known including through the UN Universal Periodic Review process and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s annual Human Rights and Democracy Report.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-20T14:44:34.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421074/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421074/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Saudi Arabia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Saudi Arabian counterpart on human rights abuses in that country.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","11654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421075","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>The UK Government is in regular contact with the Saudi authorities about the situation in Yemen through our Embassy in Riyadh and our Yemen Office based in Jeddah. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) spoke to Saudi Foreign Minister Al Jubeir on 29 September in the margins of the UN General Assembly. He underlined the importance of a political solution to the current crisis as soon as possible and reinforced the necessity of compliance with international humanitarian law. I also chaired a high level meeting at UNGA focused on pursuing a political solution.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-20T14:41:23.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421075/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421075/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Saudi Arabian authorities on pursuing a negotiated solution to the conflict in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","11624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421076","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","From 1 April 2016 the Foreign and Commonwealth Office will use the Government-wide Common Charter of Accounts, which is already in the public domain and can be found on www.gov.uk.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-10-21T14:09:35.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421076/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421076/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Accountancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will place in the Library a copy of his Department's chart of account.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421077","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>This information is already publically available. Our spend on international subscriptions has been listed under ‘Programme’ in our Annual Report and Accounts each financial year from 2000-01 to 2014-15. Our Accounts since 2004-05 are available on www.gov.uk; Accounts for earlier years are available in hard copy in the Parliamentary Library and can also be accessed on the FCO pages at webarchives.nationalarchives.gov.uk.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-10-21T14:10:22.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421077/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421077/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Subscriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department spent on each international subscription in each financial year from 2000-01 to 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421078","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-30","<p>The Global Asset Management Plan is a commercially sensitive document which, if publicly available, would put the FCO and the UK taxpayer at a severe disadvantage in negotiating sales, purchases and leases. For that reason I will not place a copy of the plan in the Library.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-10-30T15:44:42.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421078/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421078/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will place in the Library a copy of his Department's global asset management plan.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421079","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>It is not possible to provide a breakdown of UK based and Locally Engaged Staff prior to 2012/13.</p><p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office provided details of UK based staffing at posts in the Annual Accounts and Reports for 2014/2015. The latter can be found at https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/foreign-and-commonwealth-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015.</p><p>The number of locally engaged staff by post for 2014-15 is shown below [attached file].</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-21T12:23:01.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421079/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421079/answer","PQ 11569 how many locally engaged staff and UK based - table of LE Staff.docx","PQ 11569 how many locally engaged staff and UK based - table of LE Staff.docx","Number of LE staff by post for 2014-15","Number of LE staff by post for 2014-15","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421079/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many (a) locally engaged and (b) UK-based staff worked in each overseas post in financial years (i) 2000-01, (ii) 2005-06, (iii) 2010-11 and (iv) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","11569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421080","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>We are aware of reports on alleged violations of international humanitarian law (IHL) by all sides to the conflict in Yemen, and take them very seriously. We have raised our concerns over alleged IHL violations with the Saudi Arabian Government and other members of the Coalition, and in return have received repeated assurances of their compliance. We have also raised our concerns over alleged IHL and international human rights law violations by the Houthis, and again stressed the importance of compliance.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-10-20T14:39:52.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421080/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421080/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2015 to Question 6862 on Yemen: armed conflict, whether it remains the case that the UK Government has seen no credible evidence that the Saudi-led coalition has breached international humanitarian law in its campaign in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","11580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421081","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>I was sorry to hear of Mr Boehner’s resignation. He has been a good friend to the UK and a strong advocate of the transatlantic relationship. It is unclear at this stage who the next Speaker will be but we remain confident that, whomever is selected, the UK-US relationship will remain as vibrant and strong as ever. We look forward to working with his successor.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-10-20T14:37:34.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421081/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421081/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-10-13","USA: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of John Boehner's resignation as US Congress Speaker on US-UK relations.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421082","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p>We have written to Derek Brown, Chair of the Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s enquiry. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","11730","2015-10-16T13:15:50.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421082/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421082/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients Lancashire Care have admitted to named NHS facilities at (a) Clatterbridge, (b) West Part, Darlington, (c) Hull (d) Birch Hill, Rochdale, (e) Brierley and (f) other named facilities between 1 January and 30 September 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","11729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421083","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p>We have written to Derek Brown, Chair of the Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s enquiry. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","11729","2015-10-16T13:15:50.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421083/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421083/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust have admitted to named private facilities at (a) Cygnet, Bierley, (b) Cygnet, Bradford, (c) Cygnet, Harrogate, (d) Cygnet, Harrow, (e) Cygnet, Wyke, (f) The Priory, Cheadle Royal, (g) The Priory, Darlington, (h) The Priory, Glasgow, (i) The Priory, Altringham, (j) The Spinney, Manchester and (k) other facilities between 1 January and 30 September 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","11730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421084","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>Public Health England is responsible for collecting cancer data to support national cancer registration in England, and recognises the importance of collecting data on recurrent breast cancer. At present pilot work in acute trusts has improved the reporting for breast cancer recurrence and metastasis totheNational CancerRegistration Service,but the data is not complete. Further work is being scoped by NHS England and Public Health England based on the recommendation in the recent Independent Cancer Taskforce report to establish robust surveillance systems to collect this data on all cancers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-16T11:43:55.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421084/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421084/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Breast Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to establish a database of people suffering from secondary breast cancer; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","11731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421085","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care providers in England. The CQC is responsible for assessing whether providers are meeting the fundamental standards. The CQC provided the following information:</p><br /><p>Since the introduction of the CQC’s new inspection regime in September 2013 the CQC has conducted 34 ratings inspections across NHS mental health providers (these providers have 639 separate locations). This is around two thirds of all NHS providers with a primary inspection category of mental health registered with CQC. The CQC has also conducted 99 inspections across independent mental health locations, including substance misuse services.</p><br /><p>The CQC is unable to provide a detailed breakdown of data prior to September 2013 when the new style of inspection was introduced due to the disproportionate cost of compiling this data.</p><br /><p>There are a number of mental health locations that have not been inspected since 2010. When inspecting NHS mental health providers CQC does not necessarily inspect every single location.</p><br /><p>The focus of all CQC inspections is on the quality and safety of services, based on the things that matter to people. We always ask the following five key questions of services: Are they safe? Are they effective? Are they caring? Are they responsive to people’s needs? Are they well-led?</p><br /><p>The CQC expects to complete its inspections of mental health providers by the end of June 2016, with the exception of intendent standalone substance misuse services, which are on a longer timetable as we have just begun to roll out our new approach to these services.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","11781","2015-10-16T16:49:02.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421085/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421085/answer","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421085/answer/previousversion/23904","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421085/answer/previousversion/23904",,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Mental Health Services: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what (a) proportion and (b) number of mental health providers have been inspected by the Care Quality Commission under its new inspection regime.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","11780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421086","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care providers in England. The CQC is responsible for assessing whether providers are meeting the fundamental standards. The CQC provided the following information:</p><br /><p>Since the introduction of the CQC’s new inspection regime in September 2013 the CQC has conducted 34 ratings inspections across NHS mental health providers (these providers have 639 separate locations). This is around two thirds of all NHS providers with a primary inspection category of mental health registered with CQC. The CQC has also conducted 99 inspections across independent mental health locations, including substance misuse services.</p><br /><p>The CQC is unable to provide a detailed breakdown of data prior to September 2013 when the new style of inspection was introduced due to the disproportionate cost of compiling this data.</p><br /><p>There are a number of mental health locations that have not been inspected since 2010. When inspecting NHS mental health providers CQC does not necessarily inspect every single location.</p><br /><p>The focus of all CQC inspections is on the quality and safety of services, based on the things that matter to people. We always ask the following five key questions of services: Are they safe? Are they effective? Are they caring? Are they responsive to people’s needs? Are they well-led?</p><br /><p>The CQC expects to complete its inspections of mental health providers by the end of June 2016, with the exception of intendent standalone substance misuse services, which are on a longer timetable as we have just begun to roll out our new approach to these services.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","11780","2015-10-16T16:49:05.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421086/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421086/answer","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421086/answer/previousversion/23903","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421086/answer/previousversion/23903",,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Mental Health Services: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many mental health providers have been inspected by the Care Quality Commission in each of the last five years; and what the longest period of time is that a mental health provider has been without inspection since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","11781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421087","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>Junior doctors play a vital role in our National Health Service and deserve a professional and fair contract that supports patient care. We also want to work with NHS staff to better support a seven day NHS. This is why the Government wants to reduce the number of hours worked by juniors and has guaranteed that average earnings will be maintained.</p><p>The best deal for junior doctors will be achieved by the British Medical Association (BMA) coming to the table to negotiate on their behalf. This is a view shared by the medical Royal Colleges, NHS Providers and others. To this end, the Government has provided the BMA and junior doctors with cast iron reassurances about its approach to a new contract and sincerely hopes that the BMA will return to the table.</p><p>Ministers receive regular representations from groups representing junior doctors.</p><p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State met Mark Porter, BMA Council Chair and Dr Johann Malawana as part of an introductory meeting following Dr Malawana’s election as Chair of the BMA Junior Doctors Committee (JDC). Ministers also meet regularly with representatives of medical Royal Colleges on a range of issues. At a recent meeting junior doctors working conditions were raised and the junior doctor training experience discussed.</p><p>Recent written representations on junior doctors working conditions have been received by Ministers from:</p><p>Dr Mark Porter, BMA Council chair and Dr Johann Malawana, BMA JDC chair.</p><p>Professor Maureen Baker, Chair of the Royal College of General Practitioners Council.</p><p>Dr Clifford Mann, President of the Royal College of Emergency Medicine, on behalf of ten royal college presidents.</p><p>Professor Sir Simon Wessely, President of the Royal college of Psychiatrists.</p><p>A related e-petition with created by M J Peluso has been published at the following link: <a href="https://petition.parliament.uk/petitions/108782" target="_blank">https://petition.parliament.uk/petitions/108782</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-10-16T12:48:58.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421087/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421087/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Junior Doctors: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent representations he has received from groups representing junior doctors on their current working conditions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","11738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421088","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>As the professional regulators it is the responsibility of the General Medical Council (GMC) and Nursing and Midwifery Council to set the standards and outcomes for education and training and approve training curricular to ensure newly qualified doctors and nurses are equipped with the knowledge, skills and attitudes to provide high quality patient care.This includes Mental Health training as required.</p><p>Health Education England will work with bodies that set curricula such as the GMC and the Royal Colleges to seek to ensure training meets the needs of patients.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-10-16T12:51:19.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421088/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421088/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Mental Health Services: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hours of mental health training is required as part of the mandatory training course for (a) student doctors, (b) student nurses and (c) midwives.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","11782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421089","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>On 3 August 2015, NHS England and the National Collaborating Centre for Mental Health published a commissioning guide for clinical commissioning groups that will set out how to prepare for the access and waiting time standard for Children and Young People with an Eating Disorder ready for implementation of the standard. The standard is that children and young people with eating disorders should be seen within four weeks or one week in urgent cases.</p><p>From January 2016, compliance with this standard will be monitored via the Health and Social Care Information Centre website based on the data collected through the Mental Health Services Data Set. This will provide a baseline for planning and implementation from 2017-2018, when the standard will come into force. From 2016, the data will be used to measure progress with a view to 95% of young people meeting the standard by 2020.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-10-16T12:13:29.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421089/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421089/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Eating Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department has taken to prepare for the implementation of waiting time standards for eating disorder services in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","11783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421090","Department of Health","true","2015-10-16","<p>Information on the proportion of people referred for talking therapies who received cognitive behavioural therapy during 2013/14 is given on the attached table <em>Proportion of Improving Access to Psychological Therapies (IAPT) referrals that finished a course of treatment between 1<sup>st</sup> April 2013 and 31<sup>st</sup> March 2014, for selected therapy types, England</em>. Information for previous years is not available centrally. Information on 2014/15 will be published in November 2015.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-10-16T12:56:33.063Z","2015-10-16T13:29:49.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421090/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421090/answer","PQ 11784 IAPT referrals 2013-14.xlsx","PQ 11784 IAPT referrals 2013-14.xlsx","IAPT Referrals for Selected Therapy Types 2013-14","IAPT Referrals for Selected Therapy Types 2013-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421090/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421090/answer/previousversion/23809","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421090/answer/previousversion/23809",,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of people referred for talking therapies received cognitive behaviour therapy in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","11784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421091","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Government is currently undertaking the Spending Review which will set budgets for the Department of Health - along with other parts of the public services- for the remainder of the parliament. The outcomes of the Spending Review will be announced on 25 November. Further details are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/spending-review-2015-a-country-that-lives-within-its-means" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/spending-review-2015-a-country-that-lives-within-its-means</a></p><p><strong></strong></p><p>Improving outcomes for those at risk of and with diabetes is of great concern to this Government. Building on the National Diabetes Prevention Programme, the Department is developing its plans in this area. These will be published in due course.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-16T11:42:17.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421091/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421091/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 17 September 2015 to Question 10120, what additional funding his Department plans to make available to facilitate diabetes care in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","11760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421092","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Government is clear the reconfiguration of front line health services is a matter for the local NHS. Services should be tailored to meet the needs of the local population, taking into account projected population growth and seeking to reduce health inequalities. Proposals for substantial service change must meet the four tests of reconfiguration which are (i) support from general practitioner commissioners (ii) strengthened public and patient engagement (iii) clarity on the clinical evidence base and (iv) support for patient choice.</p><p>It is right that reconfiguration is led by the local NHS, working closely with the support of national bodies including NHS England, the NHS Trust Development Authority and Monitor.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-10-16T13:02:23.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421092/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421092/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Health Services: Shropshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to ensure that the NHS Trust Development Authority collaborates with the NHS Future Fit process in Shropshire to make a decision regarding future emergency care for that county; and if he will take steps to ensure that population growth and the level of health inequality are taken into account in the process of making that decision.","false","Biography information for Lucy Allan","Telford","Lucy Allan","11788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421093","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>NHS England is currently developingtwo policies for the provision of Everolimus – one for the Tuberous Sclerosis forComplex Related Renal Angiomyolipoma andone for SubependymalGiant Cell Astrocytoma (SEGA). This was communicated to the National Health Service in a Specialised Services Circular on 2 July 2015.</p><p>These two policies will both be considered as in-year items for the specialised services work programme for 2015/16- however, a timetable for publication has not yet been agreed.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-10-16T13:26:49.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421093/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421093/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Everolimus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what timetable NHS England has set for developing a commissioning policy for the Everolimus drug.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421094","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>Data available from the Medical and Dental Students (MDS) Survey from 2009 to 2012 shows the output of those obtaining their first registrable medical qualification from London universities as:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Output from London universities</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>1,668</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>1,650</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>1,790</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>1,713</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Higher Education Funding Council for England MDS Survey</p><p>From 2013, the MDS did not collect information on the output from medical schools.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","11617","2015-10-16T12:42:32.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421094/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421094/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Medicine: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many medical students completed their studies in London medical schools in each year from 2006 to 2009.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","11616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421095","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>Data available from the Medical and Dental Students (MDS) Survey from 2009 to 2012 shows the output of those obtaining their first registrable medical qualification from London universities as:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Output from London universities</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>1,668</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>1,650</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>1,790</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>1,713</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Higher Education Funding Council for England MDS Survey</p><p>From 2013, the MDS did not collect information on the output from medical schools.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","11616","2015-10-16T12:42:32.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421095/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421095/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Medicine: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many medical students completed their studies in London medical schools in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","11617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421096","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>Data on the number of people diagnosed with secondary breast cancer is not currently available. Public Health England (PHE) is responsible for collecting cancer data to support national cancer registration in England and recognises the importance of collecting data on recurrent breast cancer. At present pilot work in acute trusts has improved the reporting for breast cancer recurrence and metastasis totheNational CancerRegistration Service but the data is not complete. Further work is being scoped by NHS England and PHE based on the recommendation in the recent Independent Cancer Taskforce report to establish robust surveillance systems to collect this data on all cancers.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-21T14:01:41.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421096/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421096/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Breast Cancer: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people in Eddisbury constituency have been diagnosed with secondary breast cancer in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","11573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421097","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Department has discussed with NHS England the difficulties that people on the autistic spectrum can have in getting an appropriate diagnosis in a timely manner. With support from the Department, NHS England and the Association of Directors of Social Services will undertake a series of visits to clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to gather information that can be shared between areas that have arrangements in place to meet National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) Quality Standard 51 Autism: support for commissioning and those that do not, with the aim of supporting more consistent provision. These NICE guidelines already recommend that there should be a maximum of three months between a referral and a first appointment for a diagnostic assessment for autism. We expect the National Health Service to be working towards meeting the recommendations.</p><p>St Helens CCG is undertaking a review of current processes as part of the neuro-developmental pathway project, which includes autism spectrum conditions diagnosis provision and the associated waiting times for children. It is envisaged that the revised service model will be operational from September 2016, and will be in line with NICE Guidance. St Helens also co-commissions an Autism Diagnostic service in partnership with other neighbouring CCGs for adult services. Due to recent increases in demand the CCG is also working with the local NHS provider to help find solutions in regard to how waiting times can be effectively managed in order to meet NICE Guidance.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-10-16T12:11:50.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421097/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421097/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Autism: St Helens North","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps (a) his Department and (b) NHS England is taking to ensure that autism diagnosis waiting times for (i) children and (ii) adults in St Helens North constituency meet NICE guidance.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","11602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421098","Department of Health","false","2015-10-16","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence currently expects to publish its final guidance on elosulfase alfa (Vimizim) for mucopolysaccharidosis (type IVA) or Morquio Syndrome in December 2015.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-10-16T11:39:27.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421098/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421098/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Morquio Syndrome: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects NICE to publish its final guidance on the Vimizim treatment.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421099","Department of Health","false","2015-10-19","<p>NHS England has received 12 letters from hon. Members and has met with key stakeholders, including patient organisations and charities such as the Royal National Institute of Blind People and Olivia’s Vision. This followed their decision in July not to fund Infliximab (Remicade) and Adalimumab (Humira), Anti-TNF drugs, as a treatment for adults and children with severe refractory uveitis.</p><br /><p>NHS England has also been in discussion with Abbvie, a Pharmaceutical Research and Development Company which is due to report on their trial of Adalimumab in adults in early 2016.</p><br /><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is developing technology appraisal guidance on the use of the drugs dexamethasone and sorolimus for the treatment of uveitis. NICE develops its technology appraisal guidance in consultation with a broad range of stakeholders and the representations it receives in the development of its guidance will be available on the NICE website at:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/indevelopment/gid-ta10007" target="_blank">http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/indevelopment/gid-ta10007</a></p><br /><p>NICE has not received any representations about uveitis not related to this ongoing technology appraisal.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-10-19T14:02:54.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421099/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421099/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Uveitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent representations (a) NHS England and (b) NICE have received from (i) drug companies and (ii) patient groups on the treatment of uveitis.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421100","Department of Health","false","2015-10-19","<p>Patients with uveitis are usually diagnosed and treated in primary care and no data is collected which would identify how many patients with this condition are seen and treated. Information provided by the Health and Social Care Information Centre for secondary care, shows that for 2013/14 there were 7,226 admissions to hospital where a diagnosis of uveitis has been recorded.</p><br /><p>The main treatment for uveitis is with steroids, which can reduce the inflammation inside the eye. In some cases additional treatment might be needed, such as immunosuppressants.</p><br /><p>The costs associated with these drugs are around £150 per adult patient per year and £35 per paediatric patient per year.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-10-19T14:04:28.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421100/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421100/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Uveitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of people with uveitis; and what treatment is available for that condition at what cost.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421101","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<br /><p><em></em></p><p>Officials are happy to meet with these organisations and have already offered to meet Jeena International.</p><br /> <br /> <br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-21T14:04:02.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421101/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421101/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Abortion: Gender Selection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if Ministers or officials of his Department will meet Jeena International, Karma Nirvana and other organisations representing women who have been the victim of coerced sex-selective abortion to discuss the implications of his Department's assessment of the evidence of termination of pregnancy on grounds of gender.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421102","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<br /><p>Based upon latest available data (2012/13) the proportion of National Health Service spend on people over 65 was approximately 42.6%. If this same proportion is applied to the 2015/16 budget of £115.4 billion, this would indicate a total spend of around £49.1 billion.</p><br /><p>In 2015/16 the overall spend on adult social care was £14.1 billion. Of this total figure, £4.9 billion would be spent specifically on people aged over 65. The remainder of the adult social care budget, although not specifically spent on people over 65, includes significant expenditure on services which benefit them – for example support for carers and mitigation of social isolation.</p><br /><p>In addition, the Government has implemented the £5.3 billion Better Care Fund, which provides much needed investment in better integrated care through locally developed plans and putting resources where the local NHS and social services identify requirements. Much of this spend relates to people aged over 65. However, a more detailed breakdown is not available.</p><br /><p>Funding decisions for 2016/17 onwards, including spending on health and social care, are subject to the forthcoming Spending Review. This will establish the Government’s spending plans for the next five years.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-10-21T14:43:51.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421102/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421102/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Health Services and Social Services: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the likely annual cost of health and social care provision for people aged over 65 during the present Parliament.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421103","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Department is committed to publishing an analysis of birth ratios annually; the latest report was published in August 2015.</p><br /><p>Assessments were carried out to inform this analysis and Annex C of the latest publication ‘Assessment of termination of pregnancy on grounds of the sex of the foetus’ summarises the findings with further technical detail in Annex B of the publication; a copy is attached.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","11515","2015-10-21T15:09:32.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421103/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421103/answer","Assessment of termination of pregnancy on grounds of the sex of the foetus 2015.pdf","Assessment of termination of pregnancy on grounds of the sex of the foetus 2015.pdf","Sex-selective termination of pregnancy assessment ","Sex-selective termination of pregnancy assessment ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421103/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Abortion: Gender Selection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when his Department next plans to publish an assessment of the incidence of sex-selective abortion in the UK.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421104","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Department is committed to publishing an analysis of birth ratios annually; the latest report was published in August 2015.</p><br /><p>Assessments were carried out to inform this analysis and Annex C of the latest publication ‘Assessment of termination of pregnancy on grounds of the sex of the foetus’ summarises the findings with further technical detail in Annex B of the publication; a copy is attached.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","11514","2015-10-21T15:09:32.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421104/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421104/answer","Assessment of termination of pregnancy on grounds of the sex of the foetus 2015.pdf","Assessment of termination of pregnancy on grounds of the sex of the foetus 2015.pdf","Sex-selective termination of pregnancy assessment ","Sex-selective termination of pregnancy assessment ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421104/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Abortion: Gender Selection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of how widespread sex-selective abortion would have to be before it was detectable in nationally-compiled birth ratios.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421105","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<br /><p>Levels of provision of NHS funded hospice care are determined locally by clinical commissioning groups (CCGs). CCGs are responsible for ensuring that the services they commission meet the needs of their local population.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-10-21T13:58:23.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421105/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421105/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Hospices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has for future levels of provision of NHS-funded hospice care.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421106","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Department commissioned a Review of Choice in End of life Care in 2014 which considered the choices most important to people approaching the end of life, including on where to receive care and die. The Review published its report earlier this year setting out a vision for enabling greater choice. The Department is working with NHS England on how best to achieve this vision and will be setting out its response to the Review later this year.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-10-21T14:42:05.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421106/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421106/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Palliative Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what strategy his Department has for ensuring that as many people as possible who wish to die at home are able to do so.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421107","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<br /><p>The Department has not undertaken an assessment of unmet demand for palliative care beds for patients in the last six months of their lives.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-10-21T13:54:58.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421107/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421107/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Palliative Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the level of unmet demand for palliative care beds for patients in the last six months of their lives.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421108","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>In England and Wales, medical research using fetal tissue requires the consent of the woman who donates the tissue and is subject to the requirements of the Human Tissue Act 2004. It should be conducted in accordance with the Codes of Practice published by the Human Tissue Authority,which contain specific guidance on consent to the use of fetal tissue in Code of Practice 1, <em>Consent</em>.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","11520 ; 11631","2015-10-21T16:16:57.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421108/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421108/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Abortion: Foetal Tissue","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether doctors performing surgical abortions are prohibited from altering the procedure (a) in order to maximise the amount or quality of fetal tissue obtained for research and (b) for other non-clinical reasons.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421109","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>In England and Wales, medical research using fetal tissue requires the consent of the woman who donates the tissue and is subject to the requirements of the Human Tissue Act 2004. It should be conducted in accordance with the Codes of Practice published by the Human Tissue Authority,which contain specific guidance on consent to the use of fetal tissue in Code of Practice 1, <em>Consent</em>.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","11519 ; 11631","2015-10-21T16:16:57.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421109/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421109/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Foetal Tissue","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what procedures are in place to ensure that women agreeing to donate foetal tissue are not coerced, pressured or hurried into doing so and that they understand fully what it is that they are being asked to do.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421110","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>NHS England ran a restructuring programme in 2014/15. Since then, the organisation turnover rate has declined and for the last three months has been on average 3.75%.</p><br /><p>Retention issues tend to arise in particular roles or professions, for example finance, or in specific locations. NHS England has mechanisms to address the specific issues. Furthermore, NHS England conducts exit interviews with staff who leave to help understand issues which affect retention and ensure they can be addressed.</p><br /><p>In order to ensure NHS England can attract and retain high quality staff, and plan and manage natural succession, it has introduced a formal talent management process to ensure that line managers are discussing current performance, future potential, personal development plans and career aspirations with staff. This process has covered over 1,000 staff in senior and business critical roles. The organisation and senior leadership now have a much better understanding of people’s aspirations, development needs and career intentions.</p><br /><p>The organisation has also introduced a staff recognition scheme, and other programmes of work to improve health and well-being, capability development, staff engagement and diversity with the aim of making NHS England an employer of choice for talented people.</p><br />","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-10-21T13:22:04.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421110/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421110/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","NHS: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to improve staff retention in NHS England.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421111","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>Prior to 1 April 2013, individual funding requests (IFRs) were the responsibility of local primary care trusts and information was not collected centrally.</p><br /><p>NHS England holds information relating to IFRs made in relation to the prescribed services it has commissioning responsibility for. This data is available from April 2013 when the organisation was formally established. NHS England does not hold information relating to IFRs submitted to clinical commissioning groups.</p><br /><p>From April 2013 to September 2015, NHS England approved 978 IFRs. All IFR requests are considered in-line with NHS England associated policies which can be found on its website and accessed via the following link:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/policies/gp/" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/policies/gp/</a></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-10-21T14:56:50.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421111/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421111/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421111/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Medical Treatments: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many Individual Funding Requests have been granted in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421112","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>No such discussions have taken place. The arrangements in place for handling individual funding requests in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland are a matter for the relevant devolved administration.</p><br />","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-10-21T14:55:01.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421112/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421112/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Medical Treatments: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in devolved administrations on standardising the decision-making process for individual funding requests.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421113","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Department is considering wider reform of financial assistance and other support for those affected with HIV and/or hepatitis C by infected NHS-supplied blood or blood products. We are doing this within the context of the spending review and in a way that is sustainable for the future. We plan to consult on a way forward before the end of the year.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>Before the election, the Prime Minister announced an additional one-off £25 million to ease transition to a reformed system of payments for affected individuals. The Department is currently considering how that money will be used.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-21T16:18:56.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421113/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421113/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421113/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made on securing funding for patients infected with contaminated blood and for their families.","false","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng","11638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421114","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>NHS England has regularly surveyed staff opinion and experience since it was established in 2013. The most recent staff survey was conducted in July 2015 and was open to all employees of the organisation. 66% of all employees responded to the survey and the overall morale and engagement score was 63% positive.</p><br /><p>Informed by feedback from the staff surveys, NHS England launched a programme of work to enhance staff engagement and diversity, build skills and capabilities and improve business processes, as the survey identified these as issues that impact upon staff morale and satisfaction levels.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-10-21T13:49:11.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421114/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421114/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421114/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","NHS: Job Satisfaction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of staff morale in NHS England.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421115","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>The conditions applicable to grants awarded to Action on Smoking and Health (ASH) are set out in the grant award letters.</p><br /><p>ASH’s compliance with the conditions of the grant is assessed at the grant monitoring meetings held between the Deputy Director of tobacco control and representatives from ASH as well as in the final full year grant monitoring and governance reports.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-21T13:52:37.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421115/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421115/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421115/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Action on Smoking and Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what arrangements his Department has to ensure that financial grants made by his Department to Action on Smoking and Health are not used to fund activities intended to influence (a) Parliament, Government or political parties, (b) the awarding or renewal of Government contracts and grants and (c) legislative or regulatory action.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","11587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421116","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>NHS England is currently working with partners across the health system to determine how best to take forward the recommendations to improve cancer outcomes set out in the new five-year strategy of the Independent Cancer Taskforce.</p><br /><p>As part of putting in place a governance structure for delivery of the strategy, NHS England has appointed Cally Palmer as NHS National Cancer Director. She will lead the implementation of the strategy, as well as new cancer vanguards using outcomes-based commissioning to redesign care and patient experience.</p><br /><p>The Independent Cancer Taskforce’s report outlines that earlier diagnosis could contribute to saving a further 11,000 lives per year.</p><br /><p>Our commitment that by 2020, National Health Service patients will be given a definitive cancer diagnosis or the all clear within 28 days of being referred by a general practitioner, means that patients, particularly those with harder to diagnose cancers, will be diagnosed faster.</p><br /> <br /> <br /> <br /> <br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-21T16:20:15.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421116/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421116/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421116/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he plans to take to ensure that the recommendations in the publication entitled Achieving world-class cancer outcomes: a strategy for England 2015-2020 by the Independent Cancer Taskforce are implemented.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","11704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421117","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>The human papillomavirus (HPV) sub-committee of the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI), which advises the Department on immunisation matters, considered the safety of HPV vaccine when it met in June 2015. The sub-committee reviewed safety information provided by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA), as well as reports in the media and literature investigating temporal associations of the HPV vaccine to a range of overlapping syndromes including postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome (POTS). The HPV sub-committee agreed that no available evidence supports a causative link between HPV vaccination and POTS or other overlapping syndromes. It strongly supported the continued use of the HPV vaccine to prevent infection with HPV and to protect adolescent girls from cervical and other HPV associated cancers. This position was agreed by the JCVI, which concluded it has no concerns about the safety of the HPV vaccine.</p><br /><p>As with all vaccines and medicines, the safety ofHPV vaccines will be kept under continual review.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-21T16:21:45.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421117/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421117/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421117/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the implications for its policy of the potential link between the HPV Vaccine and Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome; and what assessment he has made of the effect of such a link on the progress of the Government's HPV vaccination programme.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421118","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>All healthcare organisations registered with the Care Quality Commission (CQC) should have procedures in place to allow staff to raise concerns. Staff can also raise concerns with the CQC.</p><p /> <p>The Department has also been clear that any specific allegations about gender-selective abortions being undertaken should be reported to the police.</p><br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-21T14:52:38.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421118/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421118/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Abortion: Gender Selection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what structures are in place for (a) staff in primary care settings and (b) other healthcare professionals to raise concerns about sex-selective abortions if they believe these are occurring.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421119","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>In England and Wales, medical research using fetal tissue requires the consent of the woman who donates the tissue and is subject to the requirements of the Human Tissue Act 2004. It should be conducted in accordance with the Codes of Practice published by the Human Tissue Authority,which contain specific guidance on consent to the use of fetal tissue in Code of Practice 1, <em>Consent</em>.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","11519 ; 11520","2015-10-21T16:16:57.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421119/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421119/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Abortion: Foetal Tissue","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether foetal tissue derived from abortions is used in medical research in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421120","Department of Health","false","2015-10-21","<p>We understand that Monitor is responding to a complaint made by Care UK about the procurement of elective care services at The North East London NHS Treatment Centre located at King George Hospital, Goodmayes.</p><p>We are advised that the investigation is on-going. Monitor published a statement of issues on 21 August and will publish its findings in due course.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-10-21T14:50:17.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421120/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421120/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-10-13","Barking, Havering and Redbridge Hospitals NHS Trust: Care UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made in the arbitration dispute between the Barking, Havering and Redbridge University Trusts and Care UK, over which institution will deliver services from the King George Elective Care Centre, Redbridge, on behalf of the Barking/Dagenham, Havering and Redbridge Clinical Commissioning Groups; and what steps his Department is taking to ensure that both parties receive a prompt decision by the arbitration tribunal.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421121","Home Office","false","2015-10-16","<p>Prevent priority areas are identified through a process which assesses information from police and other partners. We do not provide a breakdown of specific Prevent priority areas for reasons of national security. Each priority area receives funding for a Prevent coordinator, and is supported by the Home Office to deliver projects which address specific local risks. Following commencement of the Prevent duty on 1 July 2015 we have allocated all non-priority local authorities in England and Wales £10,000 to support implementation of the duty.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-10-16T13:35:38.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421121/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421121/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Counter-terrorism: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which local authorities are receiving Prevent strategy funding; and if she will publish the formula used for allocating such funding.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421122","Home Office","false","2015-10-16","<p>Increasing awareness of modern slavery is vital. As part of a wider programme of events being run by Non-Governmental Organisations, the Home Secretary attended the Human Trafficking Foundation’s Anti-Slavery Day Media Awards on 15 October, where she presented awards to recognise awareness-raising work by the media and voluntary sector. The Minister for Preventing Abuse and Exploitation on the same day attended an awareness-raising event at a London school.</p><p>This month we will commence Modern Slavery Act provisions to strengthen protections and support for victims. This includes a presumption about age provision to ensure that potential child victims receive specialist support without delay; updated guidance on identifying and supporting victims; and protections for Overseas Domestic Workers who are identified as victims of modern slavery. Subject to Parliamentary approval of the relevant regulations, we also intend to implement the new transparency in supply chains duty for major businesses to disclose what steps they have taken to ensure that their business and supply chains are slavery-free and to publish guidance to help business comply. On 1 November we will bring into effect a statutory duty for specified public bodies to notify the Home Office of any victims of modern slavery that they encounter, which will help to shine a light on this hidden crime. The Government will also publish its annual report on the scale and nature of modern slavery and the UK’s response to it, and the Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner’s first ever strategic plan will be laid before Parliament.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-10-16T13:38:35.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421122/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421122/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Anti-Slavery Day","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to mark Anti-Slavery Day 2015; what steps she is taking to increase awareness of the growth of modern day slavery; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mark Field","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","11727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421123","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>The National Crime Agency’s remit relating to ‘county lines’ does not focus on the conduct of individual investigations and prosecutions. Individual investigations and prosecutions remain the responsibility of local police forces. Information on the number of investigations and prosecutions relating to county lines specifically is not collated centrally.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-10-21T15:54:53.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421123/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421123/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Drugs: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many individual investigations the National Crime Agency has conducted into County Line operations; and how many prosecutions have resulted from such investigations.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","11679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421124","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>The National Crime Agency have confirmed they, and previously the Serious Organised Crime Agency, have not, and would not decline a request by a police force to support an investigation on ‘County Lines’ based on the grounds of the age of the suspects.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-10-21T16:07:40.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421124/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421124/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Drugs: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many occasions the (a) National Crime Agency and (b) SOCA have declined a request by a police force to investigate a suspected County Line on grounds of the age of suspects.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","11681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421125","Home Office","false","2015-10-22","<p>The National Crime Agency does not conduct County Lines investigations and therefore does not hold this information. However, the NCA play a critical role in tackling child sexual abuse working closely with law enforcement partners to tackle this abhorrent crime.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-10-22T10:53:05.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421125/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421125/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Drugs: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many nominals in County Line investigations conducted or led by the National Crime Agency have been under 18; and what the age, gender and regional breakdown is of each such person.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","11680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421126","Home Office","false","2015-10-19","<p>We take security extremely seriously in cases referred to us for resettlement, working closely with the UNHCR who have their own robust identification processes in place. When potential cases are submitted by the UNHCR for our consideration they are screened and considered by the Home Office for suitability for entry to the UK: we retain the right to reject individuals on security, war crimes or other grounds. For reasons of national security, we cannot provide further on the details of the screening process itself.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-10-19T16:06:12.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421126/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421126/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that Syrian refugees coming to Britain do not have criminal records or connections to extremist groups.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421127","Home Office","false","2015-11-03","<p>The Home Office is working closely with colleagues in the Department for Communities and Local Government to plan for the integration of Syrian refugees.</p><p>We are carefully considering issues such as access to English for Speakers of Other Languages (ESOL), how access to employment can best be supported and how to draw on the support offered from the voluntary sector, including refugee and disapora organisations as well as faith organisations.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-11-03T15:53:11.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421127/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421127/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans her Department has to help Syrian refugees assimilate into British society.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","11692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421128","Home Office","false","2015-10-28","<p>The Police’s National Domestic Extremism and Disorder Intelligence Unit (NDEDIU) has a role in monitoring and gathering intelligence on groups where they pose a criminal threat from domestic extremism or public disorder. If any illegal activities are taking place, the police will take the necessary action. The Governments Countering Extremism Strategy focuses on all forms of extremism, not least the hate inspired and racially motivated nature of far right and Neo-Nazi extremists.</p><p>As yet, no specific assessment of the threat from Britain First has been carried out.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-10-28T15:37:13.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421128/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421128/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Britain First","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the threat level of the group Britain First.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","11628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421129","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information. Decisions on prosecutions are for the Crown Prosecution Service in consultation with the relevant police force.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-10-21T15:57:24.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421129/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421129/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Drugs: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many prosecutions for trafficking offences linked to County Line investigations there have been to date in cases where a child under the age of 18 was trafficked to another area to distribute drugs; and what the outcomes were of such prosecutions.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","11678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421130","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>All fifteen ePassport Gates were open and fully functional at Stansted Airport on the evening of Monday 12 October 2015.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-10-21T15:39:17.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421130/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421130/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Stansted Airport: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many of the ePassport gates at Stansted Airport were fully functional on the evening of Monday 12 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","11666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421131","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>As of 13th October 2015, the prisons detailed below are holding individuals in England and Wales solely under immigration powers:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Altcourse</p></td><td><p>Bedford</p></td><td><p>Belmarsh</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Birmingham</p></td><td><p>Bristol</p></td><td><p>Brixton</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bronzefield</p></td><td><p>Bulingdon</p></td><td><p>Cardiff</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Chelmsford</p></td><td><p>Doncaster</p></td><td><p>Dovegate</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Drake Hall</p></td><td><p>Durham</p></td><td><p>Elmley</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Exeter</p></td><td><p>Featherstone</p></td><td><p>Feltham</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Forest Bank</p></td><td><p>Foston Hall</p></td><td><p>Glen Parva</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Guys Marsh</p></td><td><p>Haverigg</p></td><td><p>Hewell</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>High Down</p></td><td><p>Highpoint</p></td><td><p>Holloway</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Holme House</p></td><td><p>Humber</p></td><td><p>Huntercombe</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Leeds</p></td><td><p>Leicester</p></td><td><p>Lewes</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lincoln</p></td><td><p>Littlehey</p></td><td><p>Liverpool</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Maidstone</p></td><td><p>Manchester</p></td><td><p>Moorland</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mount</p></td><td><p>Norwich</p></td><td><p>Nottingham</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oakwood</p></td><td><p>Onley</p></td><td><p>Parc</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pentonville</p></td><td><p>Peterborough</p></td><td><p>Portland</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Preston</p></td><td><p>Risley</p></td><td><p>Rye Hill</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Stocken</p></td><td><p>Styal</p></td><td><p>Swansea</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Swinfen Hall</p></td><td><p>Thameside</p></td><td><p>Wandsworth</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Winchester</p></td><td><p>Woodhill</p></td><td><p>Wormwood Scrubs</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wymott</p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>As of 13th October 2015, the prisons detailed below are holding individuals in Scotland under immigration powers:</p><p>Barlinnie, Cornton Vale, Edinburgh, Low Moss and Polmont.</p><p>The information provided in the table above is based on management information only and has not been subject to the detailed checks that apply for National Statistics publications. These figures are provisional and are subject to change.</p><p>The Home Office do not regularly publish data relating to the location of individuals held in prison solely under immigration powers. While migration statistics are kept under review, there are no immediate plans to include the management information above.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-10-21T15:35:36.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421131/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421131/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Prisoners: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, in which prisons people are currently held solely under immigration powers; and if she will publish this information as part of the quarterly immigration statistics.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","11644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421132","Home Office","false","2015-10-15","<p>It is not possible to make available how many ePassport Gates were not fully functioning at Stansted Airport during the months of June, July, August and September 2015 on account of security considerations.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-10-15T16:31:45.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421132/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421132/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Stansted Airport: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many days any of the ePassport gates at Stansted Airport were not fully functioning at any point during the months of June, July, August and September 2015.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","11672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421133","Home Office","false","2015-10-15","<p>ePassport Gates are in operation at many ports across the UK. At present there are (a) thirty five operating across Heathrow, (b) twenty at Gatwick, (c) ten at Luton, and (d) fifteen at Stansted.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-10-15T16:32:31.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421133/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421133/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","London Airports: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many ePassport gates are in operation at (a) Heathrow, (b) Gatwick, (c) Luton and (d) Stansted airports.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","11671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421134","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>This information is not aggregated in national reporting systems. It could only be obtained by a disproportionately expensive manual case by case search to collate the data.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-10-21T15:56:19.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421134/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421134/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Immigration and Naturalisation: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many errors made by staff of her Department in recording details such as addresses and country of birth on applications for (a) naturalisation and (b) indefinite leave to remain forms have had to be corrected in the last month.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421135","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>In line with published data, statistics are available for the 12 month period from 31 July 2014 to 30 June 2015. In that period the average time it took to issue the first substantive Home Office response to a new application for indefinite leave to remain was 14 calendar days.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-10-21T15:55:23.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421135/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421135/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Immigration: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time taken was to respond to a new application for indefinite leave to remain in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","11578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421136","Home Office","false","2015-10-16","<p>The Home Office does not hold the information requested centrally. Data is held on burglaries recorded by the police at Police Force Area and Community Safety Partnership level, but not at geographic levels below that, such as ward level.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-10-16T13:39:18.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421136/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421136/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Burglary: Preston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 15 September 2015 to Question 8380, how many burglaries were reported in each ward in Preston City Council in each of the first six months of 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","11623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421137","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>The Home Office does not hold data on the number of police officers allowed to continue on full duties, placed on restricted duties or suspended following a death in police custody or during an investigation for gross misconduct. The issue of deaths and serious incidents in police custody has long been a priority issue for the Home Office and on 23 July 2015, the Home Secretary announced the launch of an independent review of this issue.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-10-21T15:51:13.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421137/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421137/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Police: Disciplinary Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police officers have been (a) allowed to continue on full duties, (b) placed on restricted duties and (c) suspended with figures following a death in custody and during an investigation for gross misconduct in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","11626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421138","Home Office","false","2015-10-20","<p>We recognise that people of all ages may be subjected to domestic abuse. We are committed to ensuring the police and other frontline agencies have the tools they need to respond effectively. On 3 March 2015, domestic abuse and coercive and controlling behaviour became specific offences under the Serious Crime Act.</p><p>In October 2015, new guidance on investigating domestic abuse was published by the College of Policing which includes abuse of older people. New training for the police on domestic abuse has been developed and piloted in Hertfordshire; and the College is reviewing risk assessment tools used by officers. In addition, for the first time all police forces must flag all domestic abuse incidents as crimes.</p><p>The Crown Prosecution Service updated its domestic abuse legal guidance in December 2014. This includes advice for prosecutors on elder abuse. E-learning is also being finalised for prosecutors on this issue.</p><p>In addition, the Care Act 2014 heralds a significant step change for adult safeguarding in England by placing it on a statutory footing and providing a greater focus on the prevention of abuse and neglect and on the desired outcomes of the individual in question.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-10-20T16:07:48.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421138/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421138/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Older People: Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the prevalence of elder abuse by family members in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","11521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421139","Home Office","false","2015-10-21","<p>In the last three years, the numbers of Syrian nationals (main applicants only) refused asylum on third country grounds were as follows:</p><p>26 in 2012</p><p>99 in 2013</p><p>66 in 2014</p><p>The Home Office publishes annual and quarterly data on asylum applications and initial decisions; this is available in Table as_01 (Asylum data tables Volume 1) of the quarterly Immigration Statistics release.</p><p>A copy of the latest release, Immigration Statistics April – June 2015, is available from https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-10-21T15:37:50.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421139/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/421139/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-10-13","Asylum: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum applications made by Syrian nationals in each of the last three years were refused on the grounds that the applicant could be returned to a safe third country.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","11523"
